00:00:56.660 --> 00:00:59.180
Please help me welcome
Dr. Dean Ornish.

00:00:59.180 --> 00:01:00.166
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:00.166 --> 00:01:03.124
DEAN ORNISH: Thank you.

00:01:03.124 --> 00:01:04.700
JACK: Dean, it
really is a pleasure

00:01:04.700 --> 00:01:07.730
to have you here today.

00:01:07.730 --> 00:01:10.220
Here at Google, we're
very, very concerned

00:01:10.220 --> 00:01:13.250
about looking at health care
from many different points

00:01:13.250 --> 00:01:13.894
of view.

00:01:13.894 --> 00:01:16.310
You actually chaired-- you
were one of the former chairs--

00:01:16.310 --> 00:01:20.000
of the Google Health Initiative
back in 2007 to 2009,

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:21.080
so you've had--

00:01:21.080 --> 00:01:22.540
DEAN ORNISH: With Adam
Bosworth and Marissa Mayer.

00:01:22.540 --> 00:01:24.665
JACK: Yeah, so you've had
a lot of good involvement

00:01:24.665 --> 00:01:26.600
with Google over the years.

00:01:26.600 --> 00:01:28.320
Let's actually start
at the beginning.

00:01:28.320 --> 00:01:31.376
You're in medical school.

00:01:31.376 --> 00:01:33.500
You're in the first, second
year of medical school,

00:01:33.500 --> 00:01:36.680
and right off the bat,
something is strange about you.

00:01:36.680 --> 00:01:40.250
What is strange about you, and
what realization did you have,

00:01:40.250 --> 00:01:42.230
and what study did you conduct--

00:01:42.230 --> 00:01:44.900
even just as a medical student,
right then and there-- that

00:01:44.900 --> 00:01:46.370
led you down this new pathway?

00:01:46.370 --> 00:01:47.870
DEAN ORNISH: I have
to say, no one's

00:01:47.870 --> 00:01:51.150
ever asked me a question about
how strange I was early on.

00:01:51.150 --> 00:01:53.270
[LAUGHTER] I guess that
would make me Dr. Strange.

00:01:53.270 --> 00:01:54.902
JACK: Yes, exactly.

00:01:54.902 --> 00:01:57.360
DEAN ORNISH: The beginning,
actually, was even before that.

00:01:57.360 --> 00:02:00.410
It was when I was in college
at Rice University in Houston,

00:02:00.410 --> 00:02:01.880
and I became
suicidally depressed.

00:02:01.880 --> 00:02:05.410
And it's a long story,
but I met a swami named

00:02:05.410 --> 00:02:07.040
Swami Satchidananda
who, when I was

00:02:07.040 --> 00:02:09.080
really ready to do myself in--

00:02:09.080 --> 00:02:11.990
because first I felt like I was
an imposter, like I was stupid

00:02:11.990 --> 00:02:14.150
and then somehow managed to fool
people into thinking otherwise.

00:02:14.150 --> 00:02:16.691
And now that I was with a bunch
of really smart people-- kind

00:02:16.691 --> 00:02:19.070
of like maybe some people
feel when they come to Google,

00:02:19.070 --> 00:02:20.360
I felt like it was
just a matter of time

00:02:20.360 --> 00:02:21.470
before they figured
out that they had made

00:02:21.470 --> 00:02:23.270
a big mistake in letting me in.

00:02:23.270 --> 00:02:25.954
But I also had a
spiritual vision

00:02:25.954 --> 00:02:27.620
that was really more
than I could handle

00:02:27.620 --> 00:02:29.480
at the time, which
was that nothing

00:02:29.480 --> 00:02:31.940
can bring lasting happiness.

00:02:31.940 --> 00:02:33.960
Nothing external can
bring lasting happiness.

00:02:33.960 --> 00:02:35.000
And so the
combination of feeling

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:36.980
like I was never going to amount
to anything, but even if I did,

00:02:36.980 --> 00:02:38.438
it wouldn't matter,
was like, well,

00:02:38.438 --> 00:02:39.710
why don't I just kill myself?

00:02:39.710 --> 00:02:40.790
Because people who are
dead look like they're

00:02:40.790 --> 00:02:41.990
happy and peaceful.

00:02:41.990 --> 00:02:45.050
And I was all set to do
that, but I got so sick--

00:02:45.050 --> 00:02:47.930
I'd run myself down so much
with infectious mononucleosis--

00:02:47.930 --> 00:02:50.204
that my parents
realized I was a mess.

00:02:50.204 --> 00:02:51.120
I went home to Dallas.

00:02:51.120 --> 00:02:54.200
And as crazy as this sounds,
as strange as this sounds,

00:02:54.200 --> 00:02:57.560
I wanted to get well enough and
strong enough to kill myself.

00:02:57.560 --> 00:02:59.674
But in the meantime,
my older sister,

00:02:59.674 --> 00:03:01.340
who had been a child
of the '60s and who

00:03:01.340 --> 00:03:04.165
had studied with this ecumenical
swami had really helped her.

00:03:04.165 --> 00:03:05.540
And so my parents
decided to have

00:03:05.540 --> 00:03:07.530
a cocktail party for the swami.

00:03:07.530 --> 00:03:10.250
Now, in Dallas in 1972,
this was pretty strange,

00:03:10.250 --> 00:03:11.390
as you would say.

00:03:11.390 --> 00:03:14.319
And he started off by
saying a little lecture

00:03:14.319 --> 00:03:15.110
in our living room.

00:03:15.110 --> 00:03:17.568
Nothing can bring you lasting
happiness-- which I'd already

00:03:17.568 --> 00:03:19.590
figured out, except I was
ready to do myself in,

00:03:19.590 --> 00:03:20.450
and he was glowing.

00:03:20.450 --> 00:03:22.280
I was like, what
am I missing here?

00:03:22.280 --> 00:03:24.314
And he went on to say
what probably sounds

00:03:24.314 --> 00:03:26.480
like a new-age cliche, but
it turned my life around,

00:03:26.480 --> 00:03:29.510
which is that nothing can bring
you lasting peace and happiness

00:03:29.510 --> 00:03:32.430
and health, but it's our nature
to be happy and peaceful.

00:03:32.430 --> 00:03:34.430
And our whole culture
teaches us that if we just

00:03:34.430 --> 00:03:37.160
get more stuff-- more money,
more power, more beauty, more

00:03:37.160 --> 00:03:39.710
accomplishment--
then we'll be happy.

00:03:39.710 --> 00:03:42.170
And he would say, once
you set up that dynamic--

00:03:42.170 --> 00:03:43.170
that view of the world--

00:03:43.170 --> 00:03:44.753
however it turns
out, you're generally

00:03:44.753 --> 00:03:47.300
going to be miserable, because
until you get it you feel bad.

00:03:47.300 --> 00:03:48.680
If someone else gets it
and you don't, then you

00:03:48.680 --> 00:03:49.420
feel really bad.

00:03:49.420 --> 00:03:52.130
And it confirms that we
have this very hostile,

00:03:52.130 --> 00:03:55.050
zero-sum game, dog-eat-dog
view of the world.

00:03:55.050 --> 00:03:57.140
But even if you get it,
it's great for the moment.

00:03:57.140 --> 00:03:58.040
It's very seductive.

00:03:58.040 --> 00:03:58.670
I got it.

00:03:58.670 --> 00:03:59.660
I'm happy.

00:03:59.660 --> 00:04:02.390
But invariably, it's
soon followed by--

00:04:02.390 --> 00:04:03.290
well, now what?

00:04:03.290 --> 00:04:04.630
It's never enough.

00:04:04.630 --> 00:04:05.380
Or so what?

00:04:05.380 --> 00:04:05.910
Big deal.

00:04:05.910 --> 00:04:07.830
It doesn't really provide
that lasting sense of meaning.

00:04:07.830 --> 00:04:10.121
So then we say, well, this
didn't, but maybe that will.

00:04:10.121 --> 00:04:12.365
And one patient years
ago told me-- he said,

00:04:12.365 --> 00:04:14.240
the letdown that comes
from getting something

00:04:14.240 --> 00:04:15.980
that I thought would make
me happy was so great,

00:04:15.980 --> 00:04:18.063
I always make sure I've
got a dozen projects going

00:04:18.063 --> 00:04:20.450
at the same time so I can
immediately shift my attention.

00:04:20.450 --> 00:04:21.019
So--

00:04:21.019 --> 00:04:22.660
JACK: So you had
this epiphany moment

00:04:22.660 --> 00:04:23.930
just in the college years--

00:04:23.930 --> 00:04:24.320
DEAN ORNISH: Yes.

00:04:24.320 --> 00:04:26.840
JACK: What led you to decide,
then, to go to medical school?

00:04:26.840 --> 00:04:28.310
DEAN ORNISH: Well, I always
wanted to go to medical school.

00:04:28.310 --> 00:04:30.159
Actually, I was going
to be a photographer,

00:04:30.159 --> 00:04:32.450
and there was a photographer
named Philippe Halsman who

00:04:32.450 --> 00:04:35.360
did over 100 "LIFE" magazine
covers in the heyday of life.

00:04:35.360 --> 00:04:36.725
And I said, I want to be
a photographer like you.

00:04:36.725 --> 00:04:37.880
He said, oh, no, don't
be a photographer.

00:04:37.880 --> 00:04:38.754
It's a terrible life.

00:04:38.754 --> 00:04:39.639
Be a doctor.

00:04:39.639 --> 00:04:41.180
So then you can take
all the pictures

00:04:41.180 --> 00:04:42.320
you want and you don't have
to worry about pleasing

00:04:42.320 --> 00:04:43.729
an editor and so on.

00:04:43.729 --> 00:04:45.770
But I actually always
wanted to be a doctor, too.

00:04:45.770 --> 00:04:48.471
And so I went from not being
able to read the headline

00:04:48.471 --> 00:04:49.970
on a newspaper when
I was in college

00:04:49.970 --> 00:04:52.469
and tell you five minutes later
what it said to doing really

00:04:52.469 --> 00:04:54.110
well and graduating
first in my class

00:04:54.110 --> 00:04:55.985
and giving the baccalaureate
and all of that.

00:04:55.985 --> 00:04:59.390
And I say that just to say
how powerful these beliefs are

00:04:59.390 --> 00:05:01.766
for better and for worse
and affecting our lives.

00:05:01.766 --> 00:05:03.140
So when I went to
medical school,

00:05:03.140 --> 00:05:05.420
I was learning how to do bypass
surgery with Michael DeBakey

00:05:05.420 --> 00:05:07.795
the heart surgeon, who was
one of the inventors of bypass

00:05:07.795 --> 00:05:08.570
surgery.

00:05:08.570 --> 00:05:09.560
And we cut people open.

00:05:09.560 --> 00:05:10.970
We bypass their
clogged arteries.

00:05:10.970 --> 00:05:12.440
You tell them they were cured.

00:05:12.440 --> 00:05:13.760
And more often than
not, they would go home

00:05:13.760 --> 00:05:15.120
and do all the things that
had caused the problem

00:05:15.120 --> 00:05:15.980
in the first place--

00:05:15.980 --> 00:05:18.320
eat junk food, smoke cigarettes,
not manage stress, not

00:05:18.320 --> 00:05:19.490
exercise.

00:05:19.490 --> 00:05:21.710
And their new bypasses
would clog up,

00:05:21.710 --> 00:05:24.530
and we'd cut them open again,
sometimes multiple times.

00:05:24.530 --> 00:05:27.200
So that, for me, became the
metaphor-- the paradigm,

00:05:27.200 --> 00:05:30.020
or the guiding principle that
all of my work for the next 40

00:05:30.020 --> 00:05:31.464
years, which is that--

00:05:31.464 --> 00:05:33.380
instead of literally or
figuratively bypassing

00:05:33.380 --> 00:05:35.252
the problem, let's
treat the cause.

00:05:35.252 --> 00:05:36.710
Sometimes when I
lecture, I'll show

00:05:36.710 --> 00:05:39.050
a cartoon of doctors mopping up
the floor around a sink that's

00:05:39.050 --> 00:05:41.330
overflowing, and no one's
turning off the faucet.

00:05:41.330 --> 00:05:43.070
And the idea is that
what we're finding

00:05:43.070 --> 00:05:45.950
is the more diseases
we study, the more

00:05:45.950 --> 00:05:48.872
underlying biological
mechanisms we do research on,

00:05:48.872 --> 00:05:50.330
the more reasons
we have to explain

00:05:50.330 --> 00:05:52.670
why these simple
changes are so powerful

00:05:52.670 --> 00:05:54.560
and how quickly
people can get better

00:05:54.560 --> 00:05:56.300
to the degree they
make them at any age.

00:05:56.300 --> 00:05:59.630
It's an incredibly powerful
and motivating and empowering

00:05:59.630 --> 00:06:00.180
message.

00:06:00.180 --> 00:06:02.620
So we were able to
show for the first time

00:06:02.620 --> 00:06:04.370
that heart disease
was reversible,

00:06:04.370 --> 00:06:07.757
that diabetes and high blood
pressure and high cholesterol.

00:06:07.757 --> 00:06:09.340
People get put on
these drugs and they

00:06:09.340 --> 00:06:10.610
say, doctor, how long
do I have to take these?

00:06:10.610 --> 00:06:11.984
What does the
doctor usually say?

00:06:11.984 --> 00:06:12.610
Forever, right?

00:06:12.610 --> 00:06:14.030
How long do I have
to mop up the floor?

00:06:14.030 --> 00:06:15.654
Well, why don't we
turn off the faucet?

00:06:15.654 --> 00:06:17.500
So we can routinely
reduce or get

00:06:17.500 --> 00:06:18.910
people off of these medications.

00:06:18.910 --> 00:06:21.220
We can reverse heart
disease, diabetes.

00:06:21.220 --> 00:06:23.380
It turns out, now,
that getting your blood

00:06:23.380 --> 00:06:25.300
sugar down-- half
the population today

00:06:25.300 --> 00:06:26.694
is diabetic or pre-diabetic.

00:06:26.694 --> 00:06:28.360
Getting your blood
sugar down with drugs

00:06:28.360 --> 00:06:30.760
doesn't really prevent all
the horrible complications--

00:06:30.760 --> 00:06:33.320
blindness and amputations
and heart attacks

00:06:33.320 --> 00:06:34.642
and impotence and so on.

00:06:34.642 --> 00:06:36.100
Getting it down
with lifestyle, you

00:06:36.100 --> 00:06:37.720
can prevent virtually
all of them.

00:06:37.720 --> 00:06:39.120
And the same is true
for prostate cancer.

00:06:39.120 --> 00:06:40.495
JACK: But back
then, in the '70s,

00:06:40.495 --> 00:06:42.670
when you first had some
of these realizations,

00:06:42.670 --> 00:06:45.940
it was really almost heresy
to say that you could stop,

00:06:45.940 --> 00:06:47.500
let alone reverse,
heart disease.

00:06:47.500 --> 00:06:47.750
DEAN ORNISH: Oh, yeah.

00:06:47.750 --> 00:06:49.208
JACK: I mean, in
a sense, would you

00:06:49.208 --> 00:06:53.860
say it was a naivete of somebody
just fresh in medical school

00:06:53.860 --> 00:06:56.980
who maybe didn't know better
that gave you that impetus

00:06:56.980 --> 00:06:59.469
to say, hey, I'm going to
try this and see if it works?

00:06:59.469 --> 00:07:01.760
DEAN ORNISH: Yes, that was
definitely a big part of it.

00:07:01.760 --> 00:07:04.218
And the other part was-- having
decided not to kill myself,

00:07:04.218 --> 00:07:06.220
I figured, OK, if I'm
going to choose to live,

00:07:06.220 --> 00:07:08.971
I'm going to lead a
really messy life.

00:07:08.971 --> 00:07:10.720
I need to know what's
real and what's not.

00:07:10.720 --> 00:07:12.460
I need to find out for myself,
because I didn't really

00:07:12.460 --> 00:07:14.060
trust anyone at that point.

00:07:14.060 --> 00:07:15.710
And that means I was going
to make a lot of mistakes.

00:07:15.710 --> 00:07:17.080
And I said, I can live
with making mistakes.

00:07:17.080 --> 00:07:18.904
In fact, later when
I became a doctor,

00:07:18.904 --> 00:07:21.320
most people on their deathbeds
don't regret what they did.

00:07:21.320 --> 00:07:22.940
They generally regret
what they didn't do.

00:07:22.940 --> 00:07:24.350
Because if you do
something and it fails,

00:07:24.350 --> 00:07:25.780
then you learn something
really powerful.

00:07:25.780 --> 00:07:27.010
And there's a lot
of wisdom that comes

00:07:27.010 --> 00:07:29.110
from making mistakes-- as you
know-- and learning from them.

00:07:29.110 --> 00:07:30.565
But if you don't try,
then you just don't know.

00:07:30.565 --> 00:07:32.090
So I figure, what's the
worst that could happen?

00:07:32.090 --> 00:07:34.480
So I took a year off between
my second and third years

00:07:34.480 --> 00:07:37.270
of medical school, much
to my parents' dismay,

00:07:37.270 --> 00:07:38.280
and began this study.

00:07:38.280 --> 00:07:40.090
And fools rush in.

00:07:40.090 --> 00:07:41.630
I didn't know what
I didn't know.

00:07:41.630 --> 00:07:43.520
And so I said, let's try it,
and whatever it turns out,

00:07:43.520 --> 00:07:44.280
we'll learn something.

00:07:44.280 --> 00:07:45.990
JACK: But one of your professors
was supportive of it, right?

00:07:45.990 --> 00:07:46.270
DEAN ORNISH: Oh, yeah.

00:07:46.270 --> 00:07:47.100
They were very supportive.

00:07:47.100 --> 00:07:48.010
And that was the nice
things about going

00:07:48.010 --> 00:07:49.593
to medical school
in Texas, where they

00:07:49.593 --> 00:07:50.860
have this pioneering ethos.

00:07:50.860 --> 00:07:52.092
It's a crazy idea.

00:07:52.092 --> 00:07:54.050
It's going to fail, but
you'll learn something.

00:07:54.050 --> 00:07:54.640
Go for it.

00:07:54.640 --> 00:07:55.605
We'll support it.

00:07:55.605 --> 00:07:57.730
When I went to Harvard,
it's so hierarchical there.

00:07:57.730 --> 00:07:59.470
You have to wait till
you're 40 and work

00:07:59.470 --> 00:08:00.910
in someone else's
lab for 10 years

00:08:00.910 --> 00:08:02.870
before you even get a chance
to do anything like that.

00:08:02.870 --> 00:08:04.090
And I remember, by the way--

00:08:04.090 --> 00:08:05.530
I mean, things have
changed so much since then.

00:08:05.530 --> 00:08:07.113
The idea, even, that
the mind affected

00:08:07.113 --> 00:08:09.070
the body was a crazy idea then.

00:08:09.070 --> 00:08:10.922
JACK: So take us through
the four pillars--

00:08:10.922 --> 00:08:12.380
let's start with
the heart program.

00:08:12.380 --> 00:08:13.840
And it's very similar
for the other programs,

00:08:13.840 --> 00:08:15.590
but let's just start
with the four pillars

00:08:15.590 --> 00:08:16.620
that you have now shown.

00:08:16.620 --> 00:08:18.640
And I want to talk about
the data in a minute,

00:08:18.640 --> 00:08:20.056
because here at
Google, obviously,

00:08:20.056 --> 00:08:21.730
we're very data-focused.

00:08:21.730 --> 00:08:24.100
And what's, I think, very
interesting about your program

00:08:24.100 --> 00:08:26.350
is it's not just, oh,
people are feeling better.

00:08:26.350 --> 00:08:28.450
Clinically, as you
measure their blood,

00:08:28.450 --> 00:08:31.130
as you measure their
biomarkers, through a course

00:08:31.130 --> 00:08:34.260
of a 12-week program
doing these four pillars,

00:08:34.260 --> 00:08:37.330
you're actually seeing
the biomarker data

00:08:37.330 --> 00:08:38.440
change over time.

00:08:38.440 --> 00:08:40.870
So take us through the
four different parts

00:08:40.870 --> 00:08:43.659
of how someone can go from
having heart disease, worsening

00:08:43.659 --> 00:08:46.570
heart disease, and now
stop it and then begin

00:08:46.570 --> 00:08:47.880
to reverse that clinically.

00:08:47.880 --> 00:08:49.360
DEAN ORNISH: Yeah, they
not only feel better,

00:08:49.360 --> 00:08:51.193
they are better in every
way we can measure.

00:08:51.193 --> 00:08:53.709
And we're using these
very high-tech, expensive,

00:08:53.709 --> 00:08:56.000
state-of-the-art scientific
measures to prove the power

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:58.333
of these very simple and
low-tech and low-cost and often

00:08:58.333 --> 00:08:59.516
ancient interventions.

00:08:59.516 --> 00:09:00.890
So we started with
heart disease.

00:09:00.890 --> 00:09:02.867
And we found that
in just a month,

00:09:02.867 --> 00:09:04.450
the blood flow to
the heart improves--

00:09:04.450 --> 00:09:06.820
using specthalium scans.

00:09:06.820 --> 00:09:09.640
There was a 91% reduction of the
frequency of angina, or chest

00:09:09.640 --> 00:09:10.300
pain.

00:09:10.300 --> 00:09:12.495
Most people who couldn't
walk across the street

00:09:12.495 --> 00:09:14.620
without getting pain or
make love with their spouse

00:09:14.620 --> 00:09:17.170
or play with their kids or go
back to work, within a week,

00:09:17.170 --> 00:09:18.280
are pain-free.

00:09:18.280 --> 00:09:19.900
And it wasn't just
a placebo response,

00:09:19.900 --> 00:09:21.941
because the heart was
actually getting more blood

00:09:21.941 --> 00:09:22.907
in ways we can measure.

00:09:22.907 --> 00:09:24.490
We then did a
randomized trial, and we

00:09:24.490 --> 00:09:27.149
found after just 3 and 1/2
weeks, the ability of the heart

00:09:27.149 --> 00:09:28.690
to pump blood
improved-- using a test

00:09:28.690 --> 00:09:32.350
called radionuclide
ventriculography.

00:09:32.350 --> 00:09:35.680
After my medical training, we
did the most definitive study

00:09:35.680 --> 00:09:38.912
using cardiac Positron
Emission Tomography, or PET,

00:09:38.912 --> 00:09:40.370
to measure blood
flow to the heart.

00:09:40.370 --> 00:09:42.640
And we found a 400%
improvement in blood flow

00:09:42.640 --> 00:09:44.710
compared to the
randomized control group.

00:09:44.710 --> 00:09:47.020
And quantitative arteriography
to measure the blockages

00:09:47.020 --> 00:09:49.020
in the arteries, and we
found that they actually

00:09:49.020 --> 00:09:51.010
got less clogged after
one year, and even more

00:09:51.010 --> 00:09:52.090
improvement after five years--

00:09:52.090 --> 00:09:53.140
JACK: And again,
Dean, this is all

00:09:53.140 --> 00:09:55.480
without pharmaceutical
or surgical intervention?

00:09:55.480 --> 00:09:56.060
DEAN ORNISH: That's right.

00:09:56.060 --> 00:09:56.790
The program is--

00:09:56.790 --> 00:09:58.930
JACK: So give us the four
pillars of this program.

00:09:58.930 --> 00:09:59.860
DEAN ORNISH: And
it's been the same

00:09:59.860 --> 00:10:01.880
in all of these programs, which
I'll talk about in a moment.

00:10:01.880 --> 00:10:03.820
It's basically a whole
foods, plant-based diet

00:10:03.820 --> 00:10:06.270
that's naturally low in fat
and refined carbs or sugar.

00:10:06.270 --> 00:10:07.840
It's not low fat
versus low sugar.

00:10:07.840 --> 00:10:09.280
It's really both.

00:10:09.280 --> 00:10:09.780
And also--

00:10:09.780 --> 00:10:10.890
JACK: Would you say
it's-- on the diet side,

00:10:10.890 --> 00:10:13.510
would you say it's close to the
Mediterranean-oriented diet,

00:10:13.510 --> 00:10:15.440
or how should people
think about the diet?

00:10:15.440 --> 00:10:17.564
DEAN ORNISH: It's fruits,
vegetables, whole grains,

00:10:17.564 --> 00:10:20.109
legumes, soy products in their
natural, unrefined forms.

00:10:20.109 --> 00:10:20.900
So that's the diet.

00:10:20.900 --> 00:10:23.050
The exercise is walking
a half an hour a day

00:10:23.050 --> 00:10:24.670
or an hour three times a week.

00:10:24.670 --> 00:10:27.359
Various meditation
and yoga techniques,

00:10:27.359 --> 00:10:28.650
which has been great at Google.

00:10:28.650 --> 00:10:28.960
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:10:28.960 --> 00:10:29.840
JACK: The third is meditation.

00:10:29.840 --> 00:10:30.110
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:10:30.110 --> 00:10:30.880
DEAN ORNISH: That's right.

00:10:30.880 --> 00:10:32.760
JACK: You'll be happy to know we
have meditation rooms in almost

00:10:32.760 --> 00:10:32.970
every building, so, yeah.

00:10:32.970 --> 00:10:33.910
DEAN ORNISH: I know,
and I love that.

00:10:33.910 --> 00:10:36.160
And that was one of the
things we did back in the day

00:10:36.160 --> 00:10:38.257
when we were running
Google Health--

00:10:38.257 --> 00:10:40.090
that and trying to make
healthier food here,

00:10:40.090 --> 00:10:41.500
which was fun.

00:10:41.500 --> 00:10:44.354
And the fourth is what we call
psychosocial support, which

00:10:44.354 --> 00:10:45.520
is really love and intimacy.

00:10:45.520 --> 00:10:47.320
Or if you reduce it
down even further,

00:10:47.320 --> 00:10:50.780
it's eat well, move more,
stress less, love more.

00:10:50.780 --> 00:10:51.730
That's it, boom.

00:10:51.730 --> 00:10:55.120
And the more diseases we study
and the more mechanisms we

00:10:55.120 --> 00:10:58.120
look out, the more we find that
these same lifestyle changes

00:10:58.120 --> 00:10:59.410
have impacts--

00:10:59.410 --> 00:11:00.850
to the degree people make them.

00:11:00.850 --> 00:11:03.340
We've found it to reverse heart
disease, diabetes, prostate

00:11:03.340 --> 00:11:05.151
cancer, change your
gene expression,

00:11:05.151 --> 00:11:06.150
lengthen your telomeres.

00:11:06.150 --> 00:11:07.040
JACK: Now, I want to get
to genes in a second.

00:11:07.040 --> 00:11:08.331
But first, I want to drill in--

00:11:08.331 --> 00:11:10.210
I think all of us
would really understand

00:11:10.210 --> 00:11:12.820
that changing your diet,
moving more-- yeah,

00:11:12.820 --> 00:11:15.480
definitely would have an impact
on the physiological self.

00:11:15.480 --> 00:11:17.140
But let's drill
into the second two.

00:11:17.140 --> 00:11:21.070
Let's talk more
about how meditation,

00:11:21.070 --> 00:11:25.180
these mindfulness
exercises, really

00:11:25.180 --> 00:11:27.244
affect the physiological.

00:11:27.244 --> 00:11:27.910
And talk to us--

00:11:27.910 --> 00:11:30.160
I think there was a Canadian
study called InterHealth.

00:11:30.160 --> 00:11:33.160
There's other studies that
you've cited and been part of

00:11:33.160 --> 00:11:35.140
and leading over
the years showing

00:11:35.140 --> 00:11:38.910
the physiological impact of
something like meditation.

00:11:38.910 --> 00:11:40.330
Let's talk about
meditation first,

00:11:40.330 --> 00:11:43.376
then let's move to the social
impact of friend circles

00:11:43.376 --> 00:11:44.250
and things like that.

00:11:44.250 --> 00:11:45.708
DEAN ORNISH: Yeah,
well, meditation

00:11:45.708 --> 00:11:48.880
is a powerful way of bringing
your mind to one focus.

00:11:48.880 --> 00:11:51.982
And when that happens,
your fuse gets longer,

00:11:51.982 --> 00:11:53.440
for lack of a better
way to put it.

00:11:53.440 --> 00:11:55.180
Some people say things
like, I've got a short fuse

00:11:55.180 --> 00:11:56.060
and I explode easily.

00:11:56.060 --> 00:11:57.500
Well, your fuse gets longer.

00:11:57.500 --> 00:11:58.986
Things don't bother you as much.

00:11:58.986 --> 00:12:00.610
And when you're under
stress, your body

00:12:00.610 --> 00:12:02.120
goes through the fight
or flight response.

00:12:02.120 --> 00:12:03.560
So all of your
arteries constrict.

00:12:03.560 --> 00:12:05.020
Your blood pressure goes up.

00:12:05.020 --> 00:12:06.622
Your eyes dilate.

00:12:06.622 --> 00:12:08.580
These are things that
are designed to help you.

00:12:08.580 --> 00:12:11.157
If a mythical saber tooth tiger
jumps out in front of you,

00:12:11.157 --> 00:12:13.240
you want your arteries to
constrict and your blood

00:12:13.240 --> 00:12:15.910
to clot faster, for example,
because if you get bitten,

00:12:15.910 --> 00:12:17.320
you don't bleed as quickly.

00:12:17.320 --> 00:12:21.027
But we've evolved to deal with
these intermittent stresses.

00:12:21.027 --> 00:12:22.360
So you're walking in the jungle.

00:12:22.360 --> 00:12:23.219
The tiger jumps out.

00:12:23.219 --> 00:12:25.510
Either you run away from the
tiger, you kill the tiger,

00:12:25.510 --> 00:12:25.990
it eats you.

00:12:25.990 --> 00:12:26.950
But one way or the
other, it's over.

00:12:26.950 --> 00:12:27.560
JACK: But it's done.

00:12:27.560 --> 00:12:28.774
It's not a continual-- yeah.

00:12:28.774 --> 00:12:30.940
DEAN ORNISH: Today, it's
just chronic and relentless

00:12:30.940 --> 00:12:32.150
throughout the day.

00:12:32.150 --> 00:12:34.990
And so these same mechanisms
that have evolved to protect us

00:12:34.990 --> 00:12:37.120
can harm us, or even
kill us, because it's not

00:12:37.120 --> 00:12:38.500
just the arteries in
your arms and legs

00:12:38.500 --> 00:12:40.535
that can go into spasm or blood
clots that can form there.

00:12:40.535 --> 00:12:42.040
It can form in your
heart and cause

00:12:42.040 --> 00:12:44.350
a heart attack, or in your
brain and cause a stroke.

00:12:44.350 --> 00:12:48.160
So anything that can
manage stress better--

00:12:48.160 --> 00:12:50.750
virtually every illness
has been found to--

00:12:50.750 --> 00:12:53.470
you're more likely to have it
if you're under chronic stress.

00:12:53.470 --> 00:12:56.770
And the other side of that
is the social factors.

00:12:56.770 --> 00:12:59.410
One of the real radical shifts
in our culture in the last 50

00:12:59.410 --> 00:13:01.743
years has been the breakdown
of the social networks that

00:13:01.743 --> 00:13:04.150
used to give people a sense
of connection and community.

00:13:04.150 --> 00:13:06.809
50 years ago, most people
had an extended family

00:13:06.809 --> 00:13:07.600
they saw regularly.

00:13:07.600 --> 00:13:10.030
They had a neighborhood with two
or three generations of people

00:13:10.030 --> 00:13:10.946
that grew up together.

00:13:10.946 --> 00:13:12.532
They had a job that
felt secure they'd

00:13:12.532 --> 00:13:13.740
been at for 10 years or more.

00:13:13.740 --> 00:13:15.620
They had a church or
synagogue they went to.

00:13:15.620 --> 00:13:17.619
And today, most people
don't have any of those--

00:13:17.619 --> 00:13:18.610
maybe one.

00:13:18.610 --> 00:13:20.179
And we know that
those things affect

00:13:20.179 --> 00:13:21.970
the quality of our
lives, but they actually

00:13:21.970 --> 00:13:23.050
affect our survival.

00:13:23.050 --> 00:13:24.480
And to a much larger degree--

00:13:24.480 --> 00:13:26.813
one of the books I wrote was
called "Love and Survival,"

00:13:26.813 --> 00:13:27.900
back in 1998.

00:13:27.900 --> 00:13:29.340
And it reviewed what were
then hundreds-- and now

00:13:29.340 --> 00:13:31.006
literally thousands--
of studies showing

00:13:31.006 --> 00:13:34.110
that people who are lonely
and depressed and isolated

00:13:34.110 --> 00:13:36.610
are three to 10 times more
likely to get sick and die

00:13:36.610 --> 00:13:38.790
prematurely from pretty
much everything than those

00:13:38.790 --> 00:13:41.060
who have a sense of love
and connection to community.

00:13:41.060 --> 00:13:41.230
So I think--

00:13:41.230 --> 00:13:43.330
JACK: And one of the
studies, also, that you cite

00:13:43.330 --> 00:13:46.720
looks at predictors based
in high school and college

00:13:46.720 --> 00:13:49.790
years of prediction of health
over this 40-year period.

00:13:49.790 --> 00:13:51.700
And it was the social
bonds, actually,

00:13:51.700 --> 00:13:53.980
that were very much
determining a lot

00:13:53.980 --> 00:13:55.340
of that health over many years.

00:13:55.340 --> 00:13:55.580
DEAN ORNISH: That's right.

00:13:55.580 --> 00:13:57.570
They also did a study at
Harvard Medical School

00:13:57.570 --> 00:13:58.944
where they gave
one questionnaire

00:13:58.944 --> 00:14:01.990
to a group of Harvard students
and said to rate how close they

00:14:01.990 --> 00:14:03.710
were with their parents.

00:14:03.710 --> 00:14:07.714
30 years later, only
15% of the people

00:14:07.714 --> 00:14:09.130
that were close
with their parents

00:14:09.130 --> 00:14:11.459
had chronic diseases in
midlife, and yet the majority

00:14:11.459 --> 00:14:12.500
of those who weren't did.

00:14:12.500 --> 00:14:14.380
Now, you might say, well,
how could one questionnaire

00:14:14.380 --> 00:14:14.879
do that?

00:14:14.879 --> 00:14:16.130
Well, how you--

00:14:16.130 --> 00:14:17.020
JACK: So note to the
audience-- everyone

00:14:17.020 --> 00:14:17.850
should call their
parents after this.

00:14:17.850 --> 00:14:18.750
OK.

00:14:18.750 --> 00:14:20.717
DEAN ORNISH: So
intimacy is healing.

00:14:20.717 --> 00:14:22.550
Anything that brings
us together is healing.

00:14:22.550 --> 00:14:25.090
Even the word healing comes
from the root to make whole.

00:14:25.090 --> 00:14:27.320
Yoga is from the Sanskrit
to yoke, to unite,

00:14:27.320 --> 00:14:28.450
to bring together, union.

00:14:28.450 --> 00:14:30.430
These are really,
again, old ideas.

00:14:30.430 --> 00:14:33.640
And so when we have that
sense of love and connection

00:14:33.640 --> 00:14:36.430
and community, it
not only improves

00:14:36.430 --> 00:14:38.882
the quality of our lives,
it improves our survival.

00:14:38.882 --> 00:14:40.840
More than any other
factor-- more than smoking,

00:14:40.840 --> 00:14:41.830
more than anything.

00:14:41.830 --> 00:14:43.240
And it also
interacts with those.

00:14:43.240 --> 00:14:45.730
People are more
likely to abuse them--

00:14:45.730 --> 00:14:47.230
we tend to say--

00:14:47.230 --> 00:14:50.060
at Google, there's this--

00:14:50.060 --> 00:14:53.050
we are drowning in
information, which is awesome.

00:14:53.050 --> 00:14:55.130
I just love, because I
can just pick out anything

00:14:55.130 --> 00:14:56.620
anytime I need it in Google.

00:14:56.620 --> 00:14:58.609
But information is not
enough for most people

00:14:58.609 --> 00:14:59.650
to change their behavior.

00:14:59.650 --> 00:15:00.850
I mean, if it were,
nobody would smoke.

00:15:00.850 --> 00:15:03.010
It's not like you go, hey, Jack,
I want you to quit smoking.

00:15:03.010 --> 00:15:03.550
It's really bad for you.

00:15:03.550 --> 00:15:05.440
JACK: Right, the rational
argument itself does not

00:15:05.440 --> 00:15:06.370
seem to be sufficient.

00:15:06.370 --> 00:15:06.640
DEAN ORNISH: Yeah.

00:15:06.640 --> 00:15:08.020
If I say, Jack, I want
you to quit smoking.

00:15:08.020 --> 00:15:08.630
It's bad for you.

00:15:08.630 --> 00:15:09.304
I didn't know.

00:15:09.304 --> 00:15:09.970
I'll quit today.

00:15:09.970 --> 00:15:10.895
Everybody knows
it's bad for you.

00:15:10.895 --> 00:15:12.270
It's on every pack
of cigarettes.

00:15:12.270 --> 00:15:13.919
But so then I ask,
why do you smoke?

00:15:13.919 --> 00:15:14.710
Why do you overeat?

00:15:14.710 --> 00:15:15.793
Why do you drink too much?

00:15:15.793 --> 00:15:17.150
Why do you abuse yourself?

00:15:17.150 --> 00:15:19.210
And I used to ask
patients in our studies,

00:15:19.210 --> 00:15:20.070
because we got to
know each other.

00:15:20.070 --> 00:15:20.870
I'd say, teach me something.

00:15:20.870 --> 00:15:21.610
Why do you do these things?

00:15:21.610 --> 00:15:22.651
They seem so maladaptive.

00:15:22.651 --> 00:15:24.030
And they say, you don't get it.

00:15:24.030 --> 00:15:25.030
They're not maladaptive.

00:15:25.030 --> 00:15:26.488
They're very
adaptive, because they

00:15:26.488 --> 00:15:28.660
help us deal with our
loneliness, our depression.

00:15:28.660 --> 00:15:30.580
They say things like,
I've got 20 friends

00:15:30.580 --> 00:15:32.380
in this pack of cigarettes, and
they're always there for me,

00:15:32.380 --> 00:15:33.130
and nobody else is.

00:15:33.130 --> 00:15:34.430
You're going to take
away my 20 friends?

00:15:34.430 --> 00:15:35.679
What are you going to give me?

00:15:35.679 --> 00:15:38.470
Or food fills that void,
or alcohol or opioids

00:15:38.470 --> 00:15:40.150
numb the pain, or
working all the time

00:15:40.150 --> 00:15:42.399
is a more socially acceptable
way of numbing the pain,

00:15:42.399 --> 00:15:43.704
or video games or whatever.

00:15:43.704 --> 00:15:46.120
So we've learned that it's not
enough to give information.

00:15:46.120 --> 00:15:47.865
It's not enough to
focus on the behavior.

00:15:47.865 --> 00:15:49.490
We need to deal with
the deeper issue--

00:15:49.490 --> 00:15:51.646
the loneliness, the
depression, the pain.

00:15:51.646 --> 00:15:53.770
And so we create support
groups that are not really

00:15:53.770 --> 00:15:55.705
designed to help people
stay on the diet.

00:15:55.705 --> 00:15:57.580
They're designed to
create a safe environment

00:15:57.580 --> 00:16:00.940
to recreate what people had 50
years ago-- a safe environment.

00:16:00.940 --> 00:16:02.130
I mean, right now--

00:16:02.130 --> 00:16:04.320
social networking was
supposed to really bring us

00:16:04.320 --> 00:16:05.550
all together.

00:16:05.550 --> 00:16:08.996
Facebook has, what,
1.6 billion people?

00:16:08.996 --> 00:16:11.370
But it actually has, often,
a way of making you feel more

00:16:11.370 --> 00:16:13.915
lonely and more isolated,
because most people don't--

00:16:13.915 --> 00:16:16.290
if you grow up in a family
with two or three generations,

00:16:16.290 --> 00:16:18.049
they know where you messed up.

00:16:18.049 --> 00:16:19.590
And you know that
they know, and they

00:16:19.590 --> 00:16:21.210
know you know that they
know, and they're still there

00:16:21.210 --> 00:16:21.390
for you.

00:16:21.390 --> 00:16:22.880
And there's something
really primal about that.

00:16:22.880 --> 00:16:24.415
JACK: There was an analysis
called "Bowling Alone"--

00:16:24.415 --> 00:16:25.830
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:16:25.830 --> 00:16:27.480
JACK: --which is all about how--

00:16:27.480 --> 00:16:29.480
'50s and '60s, there were
these bowling leagues,

00:16:29.480 --> 00:16:31.979
and people had their shirts and
they had their bowling ball.

00:16:31.979 --> 00:16:33.060
They had the initials.

00:16:33.060 --> 00:16:36.386
My dad has a bowling ball
still with his initials on it,

00:16:36.386 --> 00:16:38.010
and he had a bowling
league growing up.

00:16:38.010 --> 00:16:38.850
DEAN ORNISH: So that's why.

00:16:38.850 --> 00:16:40.890
JACK: But now we're, quote,
"bowling alone," because we

00:16:40.890 --> 00:16:42.080
don't have those types of--

00:16:42.080 --> 00:16:42.220
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:16:42.220 --> 00:16:43.950
DEAN ORNISH: Yeah, or you look
at someone's Facebook profile

00:16:43.950 --> 00:16:45.360
or their Facebook feed,
and it looks like they

00:16:45.360 --> 00:16:45.990
have the perfect life.

00:16:45.990 --> 00:16:46.940
And it's like, why don't I?

00:16:46.940 --> 00:16:48.481
Or their bio sketch,
they look great.

00:16:48.481 --> 00:16:50.800
They don't talk about all
the things they've messed up.

00:16:50.800 --> 00:16:52.770
And so in our support groups,
we just create an environment

00:16:52.770 --> 00:16:54.870
and say, look, let down
your emotional defenses.

00:16:54.870 --> 00:16:56.550
Just talk openly and
authentically about

00:16:56.550 --> 00:16:58.740
what's really going on
in your life without fear

00:16:58.740 --> 00:17:00.114
that someone's
going to judge you

00:17:00.114 --> 00:17:02.140
or criticize you or
give you glib advice.

00:17:02.140 --> 00:17:05.220
So somebody might say, I may
look like the perfect dad,

00:17:05.220 --> 00:17:06.974
but my kid's on
whatever-- some drug.

00:17:06.974 --> 00:17:08.849
And instead of someone
else saying, oh, well,

00:17:08.849 --> 00:17:10.349
why don't you send them
to a drug rehab program--

00:17:10.349 --> 00:17:11.819
like they hadn't thought
of that-- it's like,

00:17:11.819 --> 00:17:13.470
what feeling does
that evoke in you?

00:17:13.470 --> 00:17:14.977
And share it as a feeling.

00:17:14.977 --> 00:17:16.310
Oh, I'm really sad to hear that.

00:17:16.310 --> 00:17:17.852
Or gosh, my kids
have other problems,

00:17:17.852 --> 00:17:19.643
or I used to have a
drug problem, whatever.

00:17:19.643 --> 00:17:21.300
Suddenly, it doesn't
fix the problem,

00:17:21.300 --> 00:17:23.940
but it fixes the loneliness and
the shame and the isolation.

00:17:23.940 --> 00:17:26.730
It's the part of my program
that most people have the most

00:17:26.730 --> 00:17:27.710
apprehension about.

00:17:27.710 --> 00:17:29.910
Most people think it's
all diet, and it's not.

00:17:29.910 --> 00:17:32.850
But also, it's the part that's
invariably the most meaningful.

00:17:32.850 --> 00:17:36.144
And we have people that were
in our study 30 years ago--

00:17:36.144 --> 00:17:37.060
they're still meeting.

00:17:37.060 --> 00:17:38.880
And they didn't like each other
when they first got together.

00:17:38.880 --> 00:17:40.060
They just happened to
be going to the cath lab

00:17:40.060 --> 00:17:41.170
at the same time.

00:17:41.170 --> 00:17:43.170
Because that need for
connection and community

00:17:43.170 --> 00:17:45.330
is a primal,
fundamental human need.

00:17:45.330 --> 00:17:47.580
And even if you've just
scratched the surface of that,

00:17:47.580 --> 00:17:50.630
you can create a Facebook or
a multibillion-dollar company.

00:17:50.630 --> 00:17:54.090
So whatever people out here
are doing in the world,

00:17:54.090 --> 00:17:55.560
to the degree that
you can create

00:17:55.560 --> 00:17:57.352
real, authentic
connections between people,

00:17:57.352 --> 00:17:59.768
it's going to be that much
more successful, and ultimately

00:17:59.768 --> 00:18:00.970
that much more healing.

00:18:00.970 --> 00:18:02.910
JACK: So Dean, let's
talk about genetics now.

00:18:02.910 --> 00:18:05.640
What's interesting is,
again, people often

00:18:05.640 --> 00:18:07.650
think of genetics as
something hereditary.

00:18:07.650 --> 00:18:11.850
I have what my parents gave me,
and that's what I'm stuck with.

00:18:11.850 --> 00:18:14.400
But what you've shown is
that these kinds of lifestyle

00:18:14.400 --> 00:18:15.780
changes--

00:18:15.780 --> 00:18:18.030
not only, again, the
diet and the exercise,

00:18:18.030 --> 00:18:21.180
but the stress reduction
with meditation, the bonds--

00:18:21.180 --> 00:18:23.850
are actually changing the
expression of the genes.

00:18:23.850 --> 00:18:27.600
And so across 500 genes, both
in terms of up-regulating good

00:18:27.600 --> 00:18:29.362
ones and down-regulating
bad ones--

00:18:29.362 --> 00:18:30.820
we'll get to
telomeres in a second,

00:18:30.820 --> 00:18:32.640
but let's just talk about
those kind of studies

00:18:32.640 --> 00:18:34.870
that you've been involved
with where you've shown--

00:18:34.870 --> 00:18:39.390
again, with actual
sequencing-- to show

00:18:39.390 --> 00:18:42.114
that the genetic
expression has changed

00:18:42.114 --> 00:18:43.280
with these kinds of changes.

00:18:43.280 --> 00:18:43.860
DEAN ORNISH: Well, just that.

00:18:43.860 --> 00:18:46.200
I mean, so often, people say
to me, oh, I've got bad genes.

00:18:46.200 --> 00:18:46.783
What can I do?

00:18:46.783 --> 00:18:48.720
In fact, Bill Clinton
is a good example.

00:18:48.720 --> 00:18:51.407
When his bypasses clogged
up, one of his doctors

00:18:51.407 --> 00:18:52.365
had a press conference.

00:18:52.365 --> 00:18:53.520
He said, oh, it's
all in his genes.

00:18:53.520 --> 00:18:55.350
His lifestyle had
nothing to do with it.

00:18:55.350 --> 00:18:56.490
So I sent him a note,
and I said, actually,

00:18:56.490 --> 00:18:58.031
it has everything
to do with it-- not

00:18:58.031 --> 00:18:59.120
to blame, but to empower.

00:18:59.120 --> 00:19:00.630
Because if it's all in your
genes, you're a victim.

00:19:00.630 --> 00:19:01.580
What can you do?

00:19:01.580 --> 00:19:02.310
I said, you're not a victim.

00:19:02.310 --> 00:19:04.120
You're one of the most
powerful guys in the world.

00:19:04.120 --> 00:19:05.425
And so he began
making these changes,

00:19:05.425 --> 00:19:07.030
and he's still doing it
now, nine years later,

00:19:07.030 --> 00:19:08.370
which I think sets a
great example, whatever

00:19:08.370 --> 00:19:10.432
your politics, when a
former president who

00:19:10.432 --> 00:19:12.390
was known for not eating
particularly healthily

00:19:12.390 --> 00:19:13.290
does that.

00:19:13.290 --> 00:19:16.376
But we found that, again, it's
another example of how dynamic

00:19:16.376 --> 00:19:17.250
these mechanisms are.

00:19:17.250 --> 00:19:19.860
In just three months, we found
over 500 genes were changed.

00:19:19.860 --> 00:19:21.729
As you say, up-regulating
the healing genes

00:19:21.729 --> 00:19:22.770
and down-regulating the--

00:19:22.770 --> 00:19:24.660
JACK: So three months
of change in lifestyle?

00:19:24.660 --> 00:19:25.620
DEAN ORNISH: 501 genes.

00:19:25.620 --> 00:19:26.310
JACK: 500 genes.

00:19:26.310 --> 00:19:27.990
DEAN ORNISH: And we published
this with Craig Venter

00:19:27.990 --> 00:19:30.471
in the "Proceedings of the
National Academy of Sciences,"

00:19:30.471 --> 00:19:32.220
and we particularly
down-regulated chronic

00:19:32.220 --> 00:19:34.750
inflammation-- genes that
cause chronic inflammation--

00:19:34.750 --> 00:19:37.109
oxidative stress, and what
are called the RAS oncogenes

00:19:37.109 --> 00:19:39.150
that promote prostate,
breast, and colon cancer--

00:19:39.150 --> 00:19:40.260
just like that.

00:19:40.260 --> 00:19:41.981
Again, it's amazing
how dynamic people

00:19:41.981 --> 00:19:44.230
can get better or worse when
they make these lifestyle

00:19:44.230 --> 00:19:44.749
changes.

00:19:44.749 --> 00:19:46.290
JACK: Let's talk
about telomeres now.

00:19:46.290 --> 00:19:48.494
Talk to us-- you've been
interacting with one

00:19:48.494 --> 00:19:50.535
of the founders of the
whole telomeric medicine--

00:19:50.535 --> 00:19:51.664
DEAN ORNISH: Liz Blackburn.

00:19:51.664 --> 00:19:52.330
JACK: --science.

00:19:52.330 --> 00:19:54.797
Liz Blackburn-- won
the Nobel Prize.

00:19:54.797 --> 00:19:56.880
Talk to us about what are
telomeres, first of all,

00:19:56.880 --> 00:19:59.880
for those in the YouTube
land who may not know yet?

00:19:59.880 --> 00:20:03.810
And what findings
did you show in terms

00:20:03.810 --> 00:20:05.460
of the impact of
these kind of changes

00:20:05.460 --> 00:20:06.915
on telomeres themselves?

00:20:06.915 --> 00:20:09.000
DEAN ORNISH: Well,
telomeres are--

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:10.760
the analogy that Liz
Blackburn often gives

00:20:10.760 --> 00:20:12.800
is they're like plastic tips
on the ends of your shoelace

00:20:12.800 --> 00:20:14.383
to keep your shoelace
from unraveling.

00:20:14.383 --> 00:20:16.260
They keep your DNA
from unraveling.

00:20:16.260 --> 00:20:18.725
And as we get older, our
telomeres tend to get shorter.

00:20:18.725 --> 00:20:20.100
And as our telomeres
get shorter,

00:20:20.100 --> 00:20:22.350
our lives get shorter, and
the risk of premature death

00:20:22.350 --> 00:20:25.360
from heart disease, diabetes,
most forms of cancer,

00:20:25.360 --> 00:20:27.600
Alzheimer's, goes up
proportionate to that.

00:20:27.600 --> 00:20:29.380
Now, she had done
an amazing study

00:20:29.380 --> 00:20:31.380
with Elissa Epel where
they found that women who

00:20:31.380 --> 00:20:32.820
are under chronic
emotional stress

00:20:32.820 --> 00:20:35.130
because they were
caregivers of either parents

00:20:35.130 --> 00:20:36.750
with Alzheimer's or
kids with autism--

00:20:36.750 --> 00:20:38.820
the more stress they
felt and the longer

00:20:38.820 --> 00:20:41.075
they felt that way, the
shorter their telomeres were.

00:20:41.075 --> 00:20:42.700
And they calculated
that the difference

00:20:42.700 --> 00:20:44.241
between the high
and low-stress women

00:20:44.241 --> 00:20:50.550
was nine years in terms of--
excuse me, 17 years in terms

00:20:50.550 --> 00:20:51.584
of longevity.

00:20:51.584 --> 00:20:53.250
But what was even
more interesting to me

00:20:53.250 --> 00:20:56.010
is that it wasn't
an external cause.

00:20:56.010 --> 00:20:57.427
It was how the
women were reacting

00:20:57.427 --> 00:20:59.593
to it that determined its
effect on their telomeres.

00:20:59.593 --> 00:21:01.690
In other words, even if
you're in a bad situation,

00:21:01.690 --> 00:21:03.497
you can mitigate and
modulate that by doing

00:21:03.497 --> 00:21:05.580
the kinds of things we're
talking-- by meditating,

00:21:05.580 --> 00:21:07.140
by eating healthily,
by exercising,

00:21:07.140 --> 00:21:09.692
by having social support.

00:21:09.692 --> 00:21:11.400
And so I thought,
well, OK, if bad things

00:21:11.400 --> 00:21:12.517
make your genes shorter--

00:21:12.517 --> 00:21:14.100
I mean, your telomeres
shorter-- maybe

00:21:14.100 --> 00:21:15.436
good things make them longer.

00:21:15.436 --> 00:21:17.310
So we did a study
together, and we found that

00:21:17.310 --> 00:21:19.035
after just three
months, the telomerase--

00:21:19.035 --> 00:21:20.910
which we published in
"The Lancet Oncology"--

00:21:20.910 --> 00:21:22.542
increased by 30%.

00:21:22.542 --> 00:21:24.000
And after five
years, the telomeres

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:26.583
got 10% longer, whereas they got
shorter in the control group.

00:21:26.583 --> 00:21:28.290
It's still the
only control study

00:21:28.290 --> 00:21:30.039
showing that any
intervention can actually

00:21:30.039 --> 00:21:31.165
make your telomeres longer.

00:21:31.165 --> 00:21:33.122
And when "The Lancet"
sent out a press release,

00:21:33.122 --> 00:21:35.380
they called it "Reversing
Aging at a Cellular Level,"

00:21:35.380 --> 00:21:36.542
which I think is true.

00:21:36.542 --> 00:21:39.000
And so many of these things
that we think are in our genes,

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:40.625
we really have a lot
more control over.

00:21:40.625 --> 00:21:42.820
Again, not to blame,
but to empower.

00:21:42.820 --> 00:21:46.120
JACK: So let's talk about the
medical establishment itself.

00:21:46.120 --> 00:21:48.120
You've had a deep
engagement there.

00:21:48.120 --> 00:21:50.340
What's great is that you
went through med school.

00:21:50.340 --> 00:21:53.780
You went to Harvard for
fellowship, Mass General.

00:21:53.780 --> 00:21:56.470
And so you're deeply familiar
with the core establishment.

00:21:56.470 --> 00:21:58.140
And in fact, you've
been invited, now--

00:21:58.140 --> 00:22:00.390
over the past number of
years, particularly--

00:22:00.390 --> 00:22:02.940
to some of the key
establishments to give

00:22:02.940 --> 00:22:05.265
rounds, to actually
describe your science.

00:22:05.265 --> 00:22:07.440
So no longer is
it something like,

00:22:07.440 --> 00:22:08.910
what is Dean doing over there?

00:22:08.910 --> 00:22:10.790
You're now inside
the Cleveland Clinic.

00:22:10.790 --> 00:22:12.190
You're inside Mass General.

00:22:12.190 --> 00:22:13.770
You're inside these areas.

00:22:13.770 --> 00:22:16.260
Yet, if you look at the
curriculum of med school,

00:22:16.260 --> 00:22:20.250
if you ask most doctors till
today how they were trained

00:22:20.250 --> 00:22:21.960
and how they're
being trained, we

00:22:21.960 --> 00:22:23.787
don't see enough of
the kind of science

00:22:23.787 --> 00:22:24.870
that you're talking about.

00:22:24.870 --> 00:22:28.800
Again, not just feel-good stuff,
but core science and impact.

00:22:28.800 --> 00:22:31.200
What will it take, or
what do you recommend

00:22:31.200 --> 00:22:34.140
as a prescription, as it
were, to the med schools--

00:22:34.140 --> 00:22:36.910
as you talk to deans of med
schools around the country--

00:22:36.910 --> 00:22:38.492
what do we need to do?

00:22:38.492 --> 00:22:40.450
DEAN ORNISH: Well, it's
a really good question.

00:22:40.450 --> 00:22:42.991
I used to think if we just had
good science that would change

00:22:42.991 --> 00:22:44.580
medical practice and education.

00:22:44.580 --> 00:22:46.621
And to some degree it did,
but not nearly as much

00:22:46.621 --> 00:22:47.197
as I thought.

00:22:47.197 --> 00:22:49.530
What I finally learned-- and
I learned this the hard way

00:22:49.530 --> 00:22:50.937
when--

00:22:50.937 --> 00:22:53.520
I started a nonprofit institute
called The Preventive Medicine

00:22:53.520 --> 00:22:55.140
Research Institute,
and we've been

00:22:55.140 --> 00:22:57.264
training hospitals and
clinics and physician groups

00:22:57.264 --> 00:22:59.550
around the country and
doing research and so on.

00:22:59.550 --> 00:23:01.260
And so through that,
in the early '90s,

00:23:01.260 --> 00:23:04.230
we trained 53 hospitals
around the country.

00:23:04.230 --> 00:23:06.326
We got bigger
changes in lifestyle,

00:23:06.326 --> 00:23:08.700
better clinical outcomes,
bigger cost savings, and better

00:23:08.700 --> 00:23:10.830
adherence than anyone's ever
shown, and a number of them

00:23:10.830 --> 00:23:13.060
closed down because we didn't
have the reimbursement.

00:23:13.060 --> 00:23:15.226
So the painful lesson is--
if it's not reimbursable,

00:23:15.226 --> 00:23:16.560
it's not sustainable.

00:23:16.560 --> 00:23:17.690
JACK: So you went on
a quest-- an odyssey.

00:23:17.690 --> 00:23:18.510
DEAN ORNISH: So I
went on a quest.

00:23:18.510 --> 00:23:20.831
JACK: And it took you
what, just a few months?

00:23:20.831 --> 00:23:21.330
Joke.

00:23:21.330 --> 00:23:22.371
DEAN ORNISH: Yeah, right.

00:23:22.371 --> 00:23:24.210
It took 16 years, actually.

00:23:24.210 --> 00:23:27.096
Because I'd been working
with the Clintons since '93,

00:23:27.096 --> 00:23:28.470
and when he was
president, I also

00:23:28.470 --> 00:23:30.420
was working with Newt
Gingrich's daughter,

00:23:30.420 --> 00:23:32.530
who had had some health issues.

00:23:32.530 --> 00:23:34.800
And so we had the President
of the United States,

00:23:34.800 --> 00:23:37.110
the Speaker of the House,
20 members of the Senate,

00:23:37.110 --> 00:23:39.270
30 members of the House-- they
all said, this is a great idea.

00:23:39.270 --> 00:23:41.820
And they still took 16 years
to get Medicare to cover it.

00:23:41.820 --> 00:23:44.520
But they did, and I'm really
grateful that they finally did.

00:23:44.520 --> 00:23:47.040
JACK: Just to clarify that--
so when people now want to do

00:23:47.040 --> 00:23:49.830
these lifestyle changes
of the diet, the exercise,

00:23:49.830 --> 00:23:52.500
the stress reduction,
and the bonding--

00:23:52.500 --> 00:23:55.210
that program, now,
is now covered?

00:23:55.210 --> 00:23:57.390
Even though-- again,
highly unusual situation,

00:23:57.390 --> 00:23:59.520
because typically, most
insurance companies want

00:23:59.520 --> 00:24:02.734
to cover a pharmaceutical
intervention, a drug,

00:24:02.734 --> 00:24:03.775
a surgical intervention--

00:24:03.775 --> 00:24:04.340
DEAN ORNISH: Or a device.

00:24:04.340 --> 00:24:05.120
JACK: --but now they're
going to cover--

00:24:05.120 --> 00:24:06.960
they're covering something,
now, that is not that?

00:24:06.960 --> 00:24:07.950
DEAN ORNISH: That's
what took 16 years.

00:24:07.950 --> 00:24:09.783
And they're covering
it as a Dr. Dean Ornish

00:24:09.783 --> 00:24:11.050
program, which is great.

00:24:11.050 --> 00:24:14.980
So we partnered with a company
called Sharecare which is--

00:24:14.980 --> 00:24:17.670
excuse me-- Jeff Arnold, who
started WebMD, and Mehmet Oz--

00:24:17.670 --> 00:24:20.490
Dr. Oz-- and Don Whaley
and others, and we're

00:24:20.490 --> 00:24:23.550
training hospitals, physician
groups, health systems,

00:24:23.550 --> 00:24:26.767
and clinics around the country.

00:24:26.767 --> 00:24:29.100
And again, we're getting the
same thing-- bigger changes

00:24:29.100 --> 00:24:31.530
in lifestyle, better clinical
outcomes, bigger cost savings,

00:24:31.530 --> 00:24:32.040
better [INAUDIBLE].

00:24:32.040 --> 00:24:33.450
We're also doing these
12-day retreats where

00:24:33.450 --> 00:24:34.860
people can come from anywhere.

00:24:34.860 --> 00:24:37.318
And Medicare is paying for it,
and most insurance companies

00:24:37.318 --> 00:24:38.430
are paying for it, too.

00:24:38.430 --> 00:24:41.310
And so what I'm learning is that
when you change reimbursement,

00:24:41.310 --> 00:24:43.870
you change medical practice,
and even medical education.

00:24:43.870 --> 00:24:44.750
And it is changing.

00:24:44.750 --> 00:24:46.440
It's slower than I would like.

00:24:46.440 --> 00:24:49.489
It's been 40 years I've
been doing this work.

00:24:49.489 --> 00:24:51.030
The president of
the American College

00:24:51.030 --> 00:24:52.620
of Cardiology, last year--

00:24:52.620 --> 00:24:59.544
Dr. Kim Williams-- found
that his own LDL cholesterol

00:24:59.544 --> 00:25:00.210
was really high.

00:25:00.210 --> 00:25:01.700
Didn't want to go on statins
the rest of his life.

00:25:01.700 --> 00:25:02.430
Did a literature review.

00:25:02.430 --> 00:25:03.263
Came across my work.

00:25:03.263 --> 00:25:04.290
Went on my program.

00:25:04.290 --> 00:25:05.680
His LDL came down 50%.

00:25:05.680 --> 00:25:08.057
Wrote about it in all
the medical literature.

00:25:08.057 --> 00:25:09.390
And at the American College of--

00:25:09.390 --> 00:25:10.470
JACK: This is the head
of the American College

00:25:10.470 --> 00:25:11.300
of Cardiology himself--

00:25:11.300 --> 00:25:11.890
DEAN ORNISH: That's right.

00:25:11.890 --> 00:25:12.780
JACK: OK.

00:25:12.780 --> 00:25:14.999
DEAN ORNISH: And he
headed a six-hour seminar

00:25:14.999 --> 00:25:15.915
on lifestyle medicine.

00:25:15.915 --> 00:25:18.630
And lifestyle medicine is using
lifestyle to reverse disease

00:25:18.630 --> 00:25:20.370
and to treat it, not
just to prevent it,

00:25:20.370 --> 00:25:22.536
which I think is the most
exciting trend in medicine

00:25:22.536 --> 00:25:23.140
today.

00:25:23.140 --> 00:25:24.540
And we did a seminar
on lifestyle medicine,

00:25:24.540 --> 00:25:26.009
and over 1,000
cardiologists came.

00:25:26.009 --> 00:25:28.050
That wouldn't have happened
five or 10 years ago.

00:25:28.050 --> 00:25:31.080
So things are changing, and
it makes me really happy

00:25:31.080 --> 00:25:31.710
to see them.

00:25:31.710 --> 00:25:33.510
JACK: So we talked
about cardiology.

00:25:33.510 --> 00:25:34.690
We talked about diabetes.

00:25:34.690 --> 00:25:35.820
Let's talk about cancer.

00:25:35.820 --> 00:25:38.370
You've now shown-- you did a
series of studies on prostate

00:25:38.370 --> 00:25:40.860
cancer to begin with,
and now, I believe, maybe

00:25:40.860 --> 00:25:43.650
on some other cancers-- showing
that, again, these kinds

00:25:43.650 --> 00:25:45.612
of non-pharmaceutical
interventions

00:25:45.612 --> 00:25:47.820
did have a powerful effect,
for example, in prostate.

00:25:47.820 --> 00:25:48.370
Talk about that study.

00:25:48.370 --> 00:25:49.260
DEAN ORNISH: Well,
prostate cancer

00:25:49.260 --> 00:25:51.910
is the number one cancer in
men other than skin cancer.

00:25:51.910 --> 00:25:54.960
And there was a major study
that came out a year ago

00:25:54.960 --> 00:25:57.280
that looked at a 10-year
study of randomized trial--

00:25:57.280 --> 00:25:59.040
in "The New England
Journal of Medicine."

00:25:59.040 --> 00:26:01.373
And what they found is that
men who had the conventional

00:26:01.373 --> 00:26:03.500
treatments-- which were
surgery or radiation--

00:26:03.500 --> 00:26:04.958
didn't live any
longer than men who

00:26:04.958 --> 00:26:07.520
did nothing who had
biopsy-proven early-stage

00:26:07.520 --> 00:26:08.720
prostate cancer.

00:26:08.720 --> 00:26:10.950
And yet, the complications
of the treatments

00:26:10.950 --> 00:26:14.360
tend to maim guys in the most
horrible and personal ways.

00:26:14.360 --> 00:26:16.580
You're wearing diapers
because you're incontinent,

00:26:16.580 --> 00:26:19.790
and you can't have sex because
you're impotent, in many cases,

00:26:19.790 --> 00:26:22.500
for no benefit at
huge economic cost.

00:26:22.500 --> 00:26:25.760
So I did a collaborative
study with Dr. Peter Carroll,

00:26:25.760 --> 00:26:28.730
who's the Chair of Urology at
UCSF, and the late Dr. Peter

00:26:28.730 --> 00:26:29.300
Carroll--

00:26:29.300 --> 00:26:31.312
excuse me, Bill Fair--
who, at the time,

00:26:31.312 --> 00:26:33.770
was the Chair of Urology at
Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer

00:26:33.770 --> 00:26:33.980
Center.

00:26:33.980 --> 00:26:35.605
When you're doing
something disruptive,

00:26:35.605 --> 00:26:37.817
it's good to work with
the most respected people,

00:26:37.817 --> 00:26:39.650
because it's easier to
get things published.

00:26:39.650 --> 00:26:40.822
People believe it.

00:26:40.822 --> 00:26:43.280
And we did a randomized trial,
and we found that these same

00:26:43.280 --> 00:26:44.990
lifestyle changes
could slow, stop,

00:26:44.990 --> 00:26:47.420
or reverse the progression
of men who have early-stage

00:26:47.420 --> 00:26:48.820
prostate cancer--

00:26:48.820 --> 00:26:50.760
just the lifestyle
changes alone.

00:26:50.760 --> 00:26:52.370
So if a guy has a biopsy--

00:26:52.370 --> 00:26:54.500
their PSA goes
up, gets a biopsy.

00:26:54.500 --> 00:26:57.254
The doctor will invariably say,
you've got prostate cancer--

00:26:57.254 --> 00:26:59.420
if they have it-- and you
need to have it taken out,

00:26:59.420 --> 00:27:00.770
or you need to have radiation.

00:27:00.770 --> 00:27:02.270
But most guys don't
want to do that,

00:27:02.270 --> 00:27:04.250
but they don't want to,
quote, "do nothing."

00:27:04.250 --> 00:27:05.660
This idea of watchful waiting--

00:27:05.660 --> 00:27:07.201
waiting for something
bad to happen--

00:27:07.201 --> 00:27:09.152
is like sitting under
a sort of Damocles,

00:27:09.152 --> 00:27:10.610
waiting for the
other shoe to drop.

00:27:10.610 --> 00:27:11.410
People don't want to do that.

00:27:11.410 --> 00:27:13.035
They say, I've got
this cancer growing.

00:27:13.035 --> 00:27:14.580
I've got to do
something about it.

00:27:14.580 --> 00:27:16.340
So we give people a
third alternative.

00:27:16.340 --> 00:27:19.370
An aggressive-- if you want to
put it in more macho terms--

00:27:19.370 --> 00:27:22.010
nonsurgical, non-pharmacologic
intervention.

00:27:22.010 --> 00:27:24.724
And then Dr. Carroll has
developed these algorithms

00:27:24.724 --> 00:27:27.140
where they can monitor people
very carefully and find out,

00:27:27.140 --> 00:27:29.480
who is that 1 out of 50 people
who really would benefit

00:27:29.480 --> 00:27:31.010
from surgery or radiation?

00:27:31.010 --> 00:27:32.480
And the others can do this.

00:27:32.480 --> 00:27:35.210
And unlike most things, the
only side effects are good ones.

00:27:35.210 --> 00:27:36.770
JACK: That's great.

00:27:36.770 --> 00:27:38.150
So what is next?

00:27:38.150 --> 00:27:40.610
You've done, now,
cardiac, diabetes, cancer.

00:27:40.610 --> 00:27:42.540
Now you're thinking about
Alzheimer's as well.

00:27:42.540 --> 00:27:43.250
DEAN ORNISH: And by
the way, before I

00:27:43.250 --> 00:27:45.250
forget, if it's true
for prostate cancer,

00:27:45.250 --> 00:27:47.249
it'd almost certainly be
true for breast cancer.

00:27:47.249 --> 00:27:51.680
And Dr. Laura Esserman, who
runs the Buck Breast Cancer

00:27:51.680 --> 00:27:53.329
Center at UCSF, and
I have been talking

00:27:53.329 --> 00:27:55.370
about doing a study for
a long time to show that.

00:27:55.370 --> 00:27:57.275
And I'm quite sure that'll
be the case as well.

00:27:57.275 --> 00:27:58.020
JACK: For breast cancer as well?

00:27:58.020 --> 00:27:58.520
DEAN ORNISH: For
breast cancer as well.

00:27:58.520 --> 00:27:59.490
JACK: Great.

00:27:59.490 --> 00:28:01.700
DEAN ORNISH: So what
we did-- we just

00:28:01.700 --> 00:28:04.040
began the first randomized
trial to see if we can

00:28:04.040 --> 00:28:05.344
reverse Alzheimer's disease.

00:28:05.344 --> 00:28:07.510
People are more afraid of
Alzheimer's than anything.

00:28:07.510 --> 00:28:09.890
In fact, James Watson-- you
know, Watson and Crick--

00:28:09.890 --> 00:28:11.930
when he had his genome
first sequenced, he said,

00:28:11.930 --> 00:28:14.270
I want to know about everything
except the APOE4 gene,

00:28:14.270 --> 00:28:16.230
which is the one that increases
your risk of Alzheimer's.

00:28:16.230 --> 00:28:18.521
Because why would I want to
know if I can't do anything

00:28:18.521 --> 00:28:19.410
about it?

00:28:19.410 --> 00:28:21.590
So we think you actually
can do something about it.

00:28:21.590 --> 00:28:24.320
I think we're at a place with
respect to Alzheimer's very

00:28:24.320 --> 00:28:27.020
much like we were 40 years
ago when I first started doing

00:28:27.020 --> 00:28:28.190
research on heart disease.

00:28:28.190 --> 00:28:29.930
There's every reason
to think it'll work.

00:28:29.930 --> 00:28:32.060
There are animal studies,
epidemiological studies,

00:28:32.060 --> 00:28:34.142
anecdotal case reports,
randomized trials

00:28:34.142 --> 00:28:36.350
where they use less intensive
lifestyle interventions

00:28:36.350 --> 00:28:38.082
that could slow or
stop the progression.

00:28:38.082 --> 00:28:40.040
I think a more intensive
lifestyle intervention

00:28:40.040 --> 00:28:41.450
can actually reverse it.

00:28:41.450 --> 00:28:44.570
So we're doing a collaboration
with Dr. Bruce Miller and Joel

00:28:44.570 --> 00:28:47.136
Kaplan at the Memory and Aging
Center at UCSF, who run that.

00:28:47.136 --> 00:28:49.010
And we're going to take
100 men and women who

00:28:49.010 --> 00:28:51.680
have early-to-moderate
Alzheimer's, randomize them

00:28:51.680 --> 00:28:54.690
into two groups, put half on
the program and not the other,

00:28:54.690 --> 00:28:57.140
and compare them using
PET to look at amyloid

00:28:57.140 --> 00:28:59.810
and MRI to look at
hippocampal volume

00:28:59.810 --> 00:29:02.180
and looking at cognitive
function testing and biomarkers

00:29:02.180 --> 00:29:03.230
and so on.

00:29:03.230 --> 00:29:06.130
And we've raised most of the
money that we need to do this,

00:29:06.130 --> 00:29:07.750
so we've already started it.

00:29:07.750 --> 00:29:09.380
We just got our IRB
approval last week,

00:29:09.380 --> 00:29:10.730
and we're ready to begin.

00:29:10.730 --> 00:29:12.410
And I'm cautiously optimistic.

00:29:12.410 --> 00:29:16.160
You never know, but I'm pretty
sure this is going to work.

00:29:16.160 --> 00:29:18.234
And it runs in my
family, too, so I have

00:29:18.234 --> 00:29:19.400
a personal interest in this.

00:29:19.400 --> 00:29:21.451
And if we could show
that we can reverse

00:29:21.451 --> 00:29:23.450
the progression of
early-to-moderate Alzheimer's

00:29:23.450 --> 00:29:25.116
by changing lifestyle,
that would really

00:29:25.116 --> 00:29:27.410
give millions of people
new hope and new choices.

00:29:27.410 --> 00:29:30.062
Because when you lose your
memories, you lose everything.

00:29:30.062 --> 00:29:32.270
JACK: Particularly as-- in
society, our demographic's

00:29:32.270 --> 00:29:32.870
getting older.

00:29:32.870 --> 00:29:33.200
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:29:33.200 --> 00:29:33.860
JACK: People age--

00:29:33.860 --> 00:29:34.820
DEAN ORNISH: Exactly.

00:29:34.820 --> 00:29:37.500
JACK: --and live longer, this
is going to be more prevalent.

00:29:37.500 --> 00:29:39.166
So before we turn to
audience questions,

00:29:39.166 --> 00:29:41.990
let me just ask a very practical
question for folks here,

00:29:41.990 --> 00:29:44.227
and also watching on YouTube.

00:29:44.227 --> 00:29:46.310
In terms of the kinds of
things that people should

00:29:46.310 --> 00:29:49.310
do, in addition to the
diet, the lifestyle,

00:29:49.310 --> 00:29:52.880
meditation, stress reduction,
and the social bonding,

00:29:52.880 --> 00:29:54.777
are there certain--

00:29:54.777 --> 00:29:57.110
in terms of the diet that we
get-- the nutrition we get,

00:29:57.110 --> 00:29:58.100
I want to use-- the
word nutrition may

00:29:58.100 --> 00:29:59.141
be even better than diet.

00:29:59.141 --> 00:30:00.997
People sometimes confuse
diet for a diet--

00:30:00.997 --> 00:30:01.580
some kind of--

00:30:01.580 --> 00:30:02.260
DEAN ORNISH: A way of eating.

00:30:02.260 --> 00:30:03.770
JACK: --bizarre regimen.

00:30:03.770 --> 00:30:06.200
But the kind of
supplements that people

00:30:06.200 --> 00:30:09.230
should think about using or
not thinking about using--

00:30:09.230 --> 00:30:12.030
fish oil supplements,
good or bad?

00:30:12.030 --> 00:30:13.966
Mushrooms?

00:30:13.966 --> 00:30:14.840
I don't mean shrooms.

00:30:14.840 --> 00:30:15.470
I mean mushrooms.

00:30:15.470 --> 00:30:15.990
[LAUGHTER]

00:30:15.990 --> 00:30:17.210
JACK: What are the
kinds of things--

00:30:17.210 --> 00:30:18.530
DEAN ORNISH: Actually, there's
some good studies on shrooms,

00:30:18.530 --> 00:30:19.030
as well.

00:30:19.030 --> 00:30:21.020
JACK: What are the kinds
of things that people

00:30:21.020 --> 00:30:22.344
should or should not consider?

00:30:22.344 --> 00:30:23.760
DEAN ORNISH: Before
I answer that,

00:30:23.760 --> 00:30:25.290
let me say one thing
that I forgot to mention,

00:30:25.290 --> 00:30:27.456
which is that with all this
interest in personalized

00:30:27.456 --> 00:30:29.782
medicine, it's the same
lifestyle program that we found

00:30:29.782 --> 00:30:30.990
could do all of these things.

00:30:30.990 --> 00:30:32.750
It can down-regulate
all these mechanisms

00:30:32.750 --> 00:30:35.342
that could reverse all
these different conditions.

00:30:35.342 --> 00:30:36.800
And I think it's
because they share

00:30:36.800 --> 00:30:38.774
certain common underlying
biological pathways,

00:30:38.774 --> 00:30:41.190
although we tend to silo them
as being different diseases,

00:30:41.190 --> 00:30:43.700
they really may be more
different manifestations

00:30:43.700 --> 00:30:46.350
of the same kind of
underlying processes.

00:30:46.350 --> 00:30:49.310
Now, if you're trying to
do a targeted immunotherapy

00:30:49.310 --> 00:30:51.020
for melanoma-- like
you so brilliantly--

00:30:51.020 --> 00:30:52.790
I mean, I don't know if
you know Jack's dad-- is

00:30:52.790 --> 00:30:54.110
it OK to talk about your dad?

00:30:54.110 --> 00:30:54.620
JACK: Sure.

00:30:54.620 --> 00:30:56.330
DEAN ORNISH: Jack's
dad developed melanoma.

00:30:56.330 --> 00:30:58.350
Now, most people, when
their dad develops melanoma,

00:30:58.350 --> 00:30:59.474
they go, oh, that's so bad.

00:30:59.474 --> 00:31:00.440
I'm so scared.

00:31:00.440 --> 00:31:03.930
Jack, who's not an
oncologist, decided

00:31:03.930 --> 00:31:06.430
he would learn everything he
could about melanoma, developed

00:31:06.430 --> 00:31:09.150
a treatment-- an immunotherapy--
and his dad is cured.

00:31:09.150 --> 00:31:10.146
So that's Jack.

00:31:10.146 --> 00:31:11.520
JACK: I didn't
develop it myself.

00:31:11.520 --> 00:31:13.110
We supported other
people's work.

00:31:13.110 --> 00:31:13.950
DEAN ORNISH: Yeah,
but you were the one

00:31:13.950 --> 00:31:14.880
who actually directed that.

00:31:14.880 --> 00:31:15.980
It wasn't just
giving them money.

00:31:15.980 --> 00:31:17.640
It was actually saying,
let's study this.

00:31:17.640 --> 00:31:18.598
Let's see what happens.

00:31:18.598 --> 00:31:21.295
It was really your work
that they put into practice.

00:31:21.295 --> 00:31:22.920
So if you're doing
something like that,

00:31:22.920 --> 00:31:26.640
I think a targeted immunotherapy
or whatever is brilliant.

00:31:26.640 --> 00:31:28.620
But for the vast majority
of chronic diseases,

00:31:28.620 --> 00:31:30.203
it's these same
lifestyle changes that

00:31:30.203 --> 00:31:31.650
can prevent and reverse them.

00:31:31.650 --> 00:31:33.040
And it's not all or nothing.

00:31:33.040 --> 00:31:34.320
I wrote a book called
"The Spectrum," which

00:31:34.320 --> 00:31:36.487
was based on the finding
that in all of our studies,

00:31:36.487 --> 00:31:38.736
the more you change, the
more you improve in every way

00:31:38.736 --> 00:31:39.390
we can measure.

00:31:39.390 --> 00:31:40.860
So if you have a
life-threatening illness,

00:31:40.860 --> 00:31:41.850
that's more of
the pound of cure.

00:31:41.850 --> 00:31:43.360
You really do have
to make big changes.

00:31:43.360 --> 00:31:45.109
That's why we were the
first to proe that,

00:31:45.109 --> 00:31:46.870
because most people
didn't go far enough.

00:31:46.870 --> 00:31:48.690
But if you're otherwise healthy,
if you indulge yourself one

00:31:48.690 --> 00:31:49.830
day, eat healthier the next.

00:31:49.830 --> 00:31:51.390
If you don't have time
to exercise one day,

00:31:51.390 --> 00:31:52.473
do a little more the next.

00:31:52.473 --> 00:31:53.880
You get the idea.

00:31:53.880 --> 00:31:56.460
In terms of supplements,
the ones that I take--

00:31:56.460 --> 00:31:58.330
I take fish oil every day.

00:31:58.330 --> 00:32:01.470
I think in general, it's better
to get your nutrients from

00:32:01.470 --> 00:32:04.357
food, but I think Omega-3s
may be an exception to that

00:32:04.357 --> 00:32:05.940
if you're going to
eat fish, because--

00:32:05.940 --> 00:32:06.870
JACK: I guess
that's my question.

00:32:06.870 --> 00:32:09.286
In other words, it's obviously
better to get it from food,

00:32:09.286 --> 00:32:12.510
but what is available
to us in the average--

00:32:12.510 --> 00:32:14.850
even organic--
grocery, what do you

00:32:14.850 --> 00:32:17.310
feel is missing from
that general availability

00:32:17.310 --> 00:32:19.230
that we may want to
think about [INAUDIBLE]??

00:32:19.230 --> 00:32:20.980
DEAN ORNISH: I think
the Omega-3s and fish

00:32:20.980 --> 00:32:22.740
oil are really worth
doing, because there

00:32:22.740 --> 00:32:23.970
are no clean fish.

00:32:23.970 --> 00:32:26.880
All fish are contaminated with
either mercury, dioxin, PCBs--

00:32:26.880 --> 00:32:28.742
bad stuff in varying degrees.

00:32:28.742 --> 00:32:31.200
But when you take the fish oil,
if you take certain brands,

00:32:31.200 --> 00:32:32.670
they remove all the
bad stuff so you just

00:32:32.670 --> 00:32:33.753
have the pure [INAUDIBLE].

00:32:33.753 --> 00:32:35.642
Or you can take the
plankton-based Omega-3s,

00:32:35.642 --> 00:32:38.100
which are vegan, which is really
where the fish get it from

00:32:38.100 --> 00:32:39.150
anyway--from eating
the plankton.

00:32:39.150 --> 00:32:41.130
And then you don't get
the bad stuff, either.

00:32:41.130 --> 00:32:44.250
So I think three grams of
fish oil or flaxseed oil

00:32:44.250 --> 00:32:47.890
or a plankton-based Omega-3s
a day are a really good idea.

00:32:47.890 --> 00:32:51.375
I think that depending on--

00:32:51.375 --> 00:32:53.880
I think the probiotics,
actually-- there's a lot of--

00:32:53.880 --> 00:32:56.255
we're actually also doing some
studies on the microbiome.

00:32:56.255 --> 00:32:56.860
JACK: The microbiome.

00:32:56.860 --> 00:32:58.080
Let's talk about the
microbiome a second.

00:32:58.080 --> 00:32:58.620
Just describe that.

00:32:58.620 --> 00:32:59.180
DEAN ORNISH: Well,
you know, there

00:32:59.180 --> 00:33:00.780
are trillions of
cells in our body

00:33:00.780 --> 00:33:03.090
that we exist in a
homeostasis with,

00:33:03.090 --> 00:33:05.361
and we're just realizing
how powerful those

00:33:05.361 --> 00:33:07.860
are-- and again, how dynamic
you can change your microbiome.

00:33:07.860 --> 00:33:08.910
We did a pilot study.

00:33:08.910 --> 00:33:11.580
We found in just three days, we
could show significant changes

00:33:11.580 --> 00:33:14.110
in the microbiome in
healing directions.

00:33:14.110 --> 00:33:16.320
So I think for most
people, if you're not

00:33:16.320 --> 00:33:18.090
eating a particularly
healthy diet, taking

00:33:18.090 --> 00:33:19.464
one of the microbiome
supplements

00:33:19.464 --> 00:33:20.700
can be a good thing.

00:33:20.700 --> 00:33:22.470
The Omega-3s we've talked about.

00:33:22.470 --> 00:33:24.570
I think most people
don't get enough vitamin

00:33:24.570 --> 00:33:27.420
C in their diets, so taking
500 or 1,000 milligrams of that

00:33:27.420 --> 00:33:29.100
is a good idea.

00:33:29.100 --> 00:33:31.894
The turmeric-- I know you
like to drink turmeric tea,

00:33:31.894 --> 00:33:32.560
which we share--

00:33:32.560 --> 00:33:33.070
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:33:33.070 --> 00:33:34.000
JACK: Right here.

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:35.520
Here it is.

00:33:35.520 --> 00:33:38.330
DEAN ORNISH: Turmeric is a very
powerful anti-inflammatory.

00:33:38.330 --> 00:33:39.240
This is one of the
reasons why it's

00:33:39.240 --> 00:33:41.198
been linked with reducing
Alzheimer's, but also

00:33:41.198 --> 00:33:42.180
other conditions.

00:33:42.180 --> 00:33:44.636
Most people aren't going to
drink enough turmeric tea

00:33:44.636 --> 00:33:46.260
or eat it in their
diet-- or curcumin--

00:33:46.260 --> 00:33:48.030
so I take a supplement.

00:33:48.030 --> 00:33:54.210
It doesn't make you smell like
curry, and those were good.

00:33:54.210 --> 00:33:55.710
So those are the
things that I think

00:33:55.710 --> 00:33:57.060
most people can benefit from.

00:33:57.060 --> 00:33:57.640
JACK: Cool.

