00:38:02.020 --> 00:38:04.410
It does make it easier
for a very busy parent.

00:38:04.410 --> 00:38:05.610
You're a busy parent.

00:38:05.610 --> 00:38:06.706
You have lots of kids.

00:38:06.706 --> 00:38:08.580
You're feeding things
like that, and you just

00:38:08.580 --> 00:38:10.110
get a lot of packaged food.

00:38:10.110 --> 00:38:13.740
But it is disconnecting us
from the source of the food

00:38:13.740 --> 00:38:14.852
and where things are from.

00:38:14.852 --> 00:38:15.810
DEAN ORNISH: It's true.

00:38:15.810 --> 00:38:18.690
JACK: It's something
that unfortunately

00:38:18.690 --> 00:38:20.359
is a major challenge that--

00:38:20.359 --> 00:38:22.650
DEAN ORNISH: Well, to the
extent at least the meal kits

00:38:22.650 --> 00:38:24.459
or whatever can be used to--

00:38:24.459 --> 00:38:27.000
the meal kits are different than
the frozen foods, and so on,

00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:28.050
because you're
actually making dinner.

00:38:28.050 --> 00:38:29.360
But they just have
done the hard part.

00:38:29.360 --> 00:38:30.540
So it makes it easier.

00:38:30.540 --> 00:38:32.400
And there are studies that show
that just when the family sits

00:38:32.400 --> 00:38:34.900
down together to have a meal
together, just the sitting down

00:38:34.900 --> 00:38:38.340
together, there's better
academic performance, lower

00:38:38.340 --> 00:38:41.719
truancy, lower illness, all the
kind of things that you want.

00:38:41.719 --> 00:38:44.010
Again, it goes back to the
social factors and the power

00:38:44.010 --> 00:38:45.520
of community and family.

00:38:45.520 --> 00:38:46.020
JACK: Great.

