in a central place
which we found was hard,

00:43:16.700 --> 00:43:18.190
and particularly if they came
for a tour or retreat from

00:43:18.190 --> 00:43:20.424
different parts of the
country, they can all use--

00:43:20.424 --> 00:43:21.590
we use Zoom as a technology.

00:43:21.590 --> 00:43:26.116
But we could use Google or
anything to say, OK, between--

00:43:26.116 --> 00:43:28.240
they pick a day, like
Thursdays, from 5:00 to 6:00,

00:43:28.240 --> 00:43:29.823
we're going to have
our support group.

00:43:29.823 --> 00:43:30.460
It's 15 people.

00:43:30.460 --> 00:43:31.380
And they all chime in.

00:43:31.380 --> 00:43:33.730
I like Zoom, because whoever
is talking immediately

00:43:33.730 --> 00:43:34.570
fills the screen.

00:43:34.570 --> 00:43:36.550
Except for people who
are not very tech-savvy,

00:43:36.550 --> 00:43:38.100
it's an easy way to do that.

00:43:38.100 --> 00:43:40.630
And so that's just one example
of how technology can really

00:43:40.630 --> 00:43:44.224
be healing in a powerful way.

00:43:44.224 --> 00:43:46.140
AUDIENCE: One really
quick follow-up question,

00:43:46.140 --> 00:43:47.369
what about machine learning?

00:43:47.369 --> 00:43:49.910
So this is something I work on,
so I was just curious as to--

00:43:49.910 --> 00:43:51.435
JACK: Artificial intelligence,
machine learning.

00:43:51.435 --> 00:43:53.285
DEAN ORNISH: Yeah, well,
you're talking to the man here.

00:43:53.285 --> 00:43:55.010
He's having a conference
here for the next three

00:43:55.010 --> 00:43:55.690
days on that.

00:43:58.276 --> 00:44:01.294
What particular aspect of
that are you asking about?

00:44:01.294 --> 00:44:03.710
AUDIENCE: So one thing people
are excited about in machine

00:44:03.710 --> 00:44:05.720
learning at least, in
health applications,

00:44:05.720 --> 00:44:09.550
is trying to take image
data and try and spot

00:44:09.550 --> 00:44:12.240
sort of the progression
of diseases, for example.

00:44:12.240 --> 00:44:12.782
So-- yeah.

00:44:12.782 --> 00:44:14.240
DEAN ORNISH: Well,
certainly, we're

00:44:14.240 --> 00:44:15.656
already seeing
things in pathology

00:44:15.656 --> 00:44:20.000
that artificial intelligence
can actually diagnose cancers

00:44:20.000 --> 00:44:22.430
more accurately and
sooner than even the most

00:44:22.430 --> 00:44:23.990
experienced radiologists.

00:44:23.990 --> 00:44:26.060
But I defer that
question to you, Jack.

00:44:26.060 --> 00:44:27.710
JACK: Sure.

00:44:27.710 --> 00:44:29.810
Yeah, I would say, it's
a very exciting field.

00:44:29.810 --> 00:44:31.390
I think we're just
at the beginning.

00:44:31.390 --> 00:44:34.210
If you look at medical
imaging as an example,

00:44:34.210 --> 00:44:37.010
and there are several
projects across this campus

00:44:37.010 --> 00:44:40.190
and other startups and lots
of people beginning down

00:44:40.190 --> 00:44:43.550
this road, the good news
is I started my career

00:44:43.550 --> 00:44:46.680
in medical imaging at NIH.

00:44:46.680 --> 00:44:49.810
And it's one of the fields
that has been most digitized.

00:44:49.810 --> 00:44:54.050
So the good news is, coming
out of most major scanners--

00:44:54.050 --> 00:44:56.810
Phillips, GE, so on
and so forth, Siemens--

00:44:56.810 --> 00:44:59.264
you get a digital file.

00:44:59.264 --> 00:45:00.680
Unfortunately,
most of those files

00:45:00.680 --> 00:45:03.260
get stored away in
some data center.

00:45:03.260 --> 00:45:04.940
And no one ever
looks at them again.

00:45:04.940 --> 00:45:08.090
We're beginning now as
a technology community

00:45:08.090 --> 00:45:11.024
to begin to tap into that
and then hook that up

00:45:11.024 --> 00:45:13.190
with the electronic medical
records, which again can

00:45:13.190 --> 00:45:15.710
be our ground truth as
to what did, in fact,

00:45:15.710 --> 00:45:16.670
happen to this person?

00:45:16.670 --> 00:45:19.610
What were they diagnosed as
based on the medical imaging?

00:45:19.610 --> 00:45:22.380
And then what was the ground
truth over the next five,

00:45:22.380 --> 00:45:25.130
six years of what
actually developed?

00:45:25.130 --> 00:45:28.430
And that becomes a rich
source of supervised learning

00:45:28.430 --> 00:45:32.570
possibility for neural
networks or other models

00:45:32.570 --> 00:45:33.570
that we can use.

00:45:33.570 --> 00:45:36.500
So I do expect this
kind of technology

00:45:36.500 --> 00:45:39.214
to really enhance the
role, say, for example,

00:45:39.214 --> 00:45:41.130
of the radiologists,
where the radiologist now

00:45:41.130 --> 00:45:44.000
is not just popping
something up on a screen.

00:45:44.000 --> 00:45:46.040
I literally still
visit hospitals today

00:45:46.040 --> 00:45:47.870
where people are
printing out films.

00:45:47.870 --> 00:45:50.099
And so it's still
happening today,

00:45:50.099 --> 00:45:52.640
where rather than looking at it
in a high-resolution monitor,

00:45:52.640 --> 00:45:54.000
they're still printing out film.

00:45:54.000 --> 00:45:55.920
So that is changing.

00:45:55.920 --> 00:45:57.629
There are other parts--

00:45:57.629 --> 00:46:00.170
there are still a lot of records
that are not electronic yet.

00:46:00.170 --> 00:46:01.970
There is a lot of movement
to make that happen.

00:46:01.970 --> 00:46:03.386
And even when they
are electronic,

00:46:03.386 --> 00:46:05.060
we have to be
very, very careful.

00:46:05.060 --> 00:46:07.630
It's clear now that
we have to be--

00:46:07.630 --> 00:46:10.400
as we're ingesting
this data for the role

00:46:10.400 --> 00:46:13.430
of supervised
learning, there's often

00:46:13.430 --> 00:46:14.894
errors in terms of the labeling.

00:46:14.894 --> 00:46:17.060
And we have to be careful
about what we're training,

00:46:17.060 --> 00:46:18.090
what we're not training.

00:46:18.090 --> 00:46:21.050
We also to make sure that
we have a diversity in terms

00:46:21.050 --> 00:46:24.920
of the demographics that we're
ingesting into these AIs.

00:46:24.920 --> 00:46:27.110
And so if we're
going to do this,

00:46:27.110 --> 00:46:30.800
we want to make sure that we
have population pools that

00:46:30.800 --> 00:46:33.300
are drawn from a
wide gamut of society

00:46:33.300 --> 00:46:36.050
so that we haven't inadvertently
trained the AI to do

00:46:36.050 --> 00:46:38.000
a great job on this
part of the demographic

00:46:38.000 --> 00:46:39.860
when their medical
image is taken in,

00:46:39.860 --> 00:46:42.080
but not that part
of the demographic.

00:46:42.080 --> 00:46:45.576
And I also think it's important
to do this on a global scale.

00:46:45.576 --> 00:46:47.450
There are some initiatives
in other countries

00:46:47.450 --> 00:46:50.080
to begin to add
to this database.

00:46:50.080 --> 00:46:51.650
But it's really just beginning.

00:46:51.650 --> 00:46:54.770
So my biggest concern right
now is about diversity,

00:46:54.770 --> 00:46:58.220
is about making sure that
as we're going through this,

00:46:58.220 --> 00:47:01.655
we have a real wide
diversity of patients that

00:47:01.655 --> 00:47:02.780
are coming into this thing.

00:47:02.780 --> 00:47:03.571
But yeah, go ahead.

00:47:03.571 --> 00:47:05.540
DEAN ORNISH: Let me
say one more thing.

00:47:05.540 --> 00:47:07.905
There's a company called
Lark that Julia Hu organized

00:47:07.905 --> 00:47:10.250
with a group of MIT
people that actually

00:47:10.250 --> 00:47:12.225
does AI text-based messaging.

00:47:12.225 --> 00:47:14.600
So it feels like there's a
health coach on the other end,

00:47:14.600 --> 00:47:15.740
but there's not.

00:47:15.740 --> 00:47:18.110
And actually, you can scale
that for virtually nothing,

00:47:18.110 --> 00:47:20.443
because you don't have to
have a coach on the other end.

00:47:20.443 --> 00:47:22.220
And so it's actually
getting increasingly

00:47:22.220 --> 00:47:25.700
effective at motivating people
to make behavioral changes that

00:47:25.700 --> 00:47:28.035
can be scaled at
virtually no cost.

00:47:28.035 --> 00:47:28.930
JACK: Yeah.

00:47:28.930 --> 00:47:33.350
The one real-world example
I would also point people to

00:47:33.350 --> 00:47:36.850
in the UK is something
called Babylon Health.

00:47:36.850 --> 00:47:39.510
People in the audience
and viewing this

00:47:39.510 --> 00:47:40.850
can check out that company.

00:47:40.850 --> 00:47:43.310
That company has not
just created a fun app

00:47:43.310 --> 00:47:46.730
which you can use to engage
on your health issues

00:47:46.730 --> 00:47:47.750
and also triage--

00:47:47.750 --> 00:47:50.300
the National Health Service
of England, of the UK,

00:47:50.300 --> 00:47:52.970
uses it to actually
officially triage

00:47:52.970 --> 00:47:56.007
1.5 million citizens in the UK.

00:47:56.007 --> 00:47:57.590
And so it's actually
an official part.

00:47:57.590 --> 00:47:58.240
DEAN ORNISH: Yeah,
it's beautiful.

00:47:58.240 --> 00:47:59.740
JACK: It's one of
the first examples

00:47:59.740 --> 00:48:02.270
that I've seen of a health
service incorporating

00:48:02.270 --> 00:48:04.280
this technology in
an official capacity.

00:48:04.280 --> 00:48:05.780
DEAN ORNISH: And
by the way, TRICARE

00:48:05.780 --> 00:48:07.560
is using the AI in
their app as well.

00:48:07.560 --> 00:48:09.560
So I think we're seeing
this more and more.

00:48:09.560 --> 00:48:11.540
And I think it's really
the wave of the future.

00:48:11.540 --> 00:48:12.040
JACK: Yeah.

00:48:12.040 --> 00:48:13.790
I think we had a
question back here.

00:48:13.790 --> 00:48:15.140
Yeah, please, your
name and-- go ahead.

00:48:15.140 --> 00:48:15.681
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:48:15.681 --> 00:48:16.880
My name is [INAUDIBLE].

00:48:16.880 --> 00:48:19.940
I'm interested to know that
most people coming from India

00:48:19.940 --> 00:48:22.259
suffer from vitamin
D deficiency.

00:48:22.259 --> 00:48:24.050
And so we've been
prescribed by the doctors

00:48:24.050 --> 00:48:25.460
to take it as a supplement.

00:48:25.460 --> 00:48:27.320
What are the precautions
actually needed

00:48:27.320 --> 00:48:28.284
to mix it [INAUDIBLE]?

00:48:28.284 --> 00:48:30.200
And there are some
articles that I read online

00:48:30.200 --> 00:48:32.199
that you shouldn't take
it with this supplement.

00:48:32.199 --> 00:48:34.491
You shouldn't take calcium
supplements along with iron.

00:48:34.491 --> 00:48:35.907
There are so many
confusing things

00:48:35.907 --> 00:48:36.950
about taking supplements.

00:48:36.950 --> 00:48:37.850
Can you clarify it?

00:48:37.850 --> 00:48:39.975
DEAN ORNISH: Well, it's
not just people from India.

00:48:39.975 --> 00:48:42.470
Most people in this country
are vitamin D3 deficient.

00:48:42.470 --> 00:48:45.090
And so I think that I would add
that to my list of supplements

00:48:45.090 --> 00:48:50.452
for most people is take 1,000
units of vitamin D every day.

00:48:50.452 --> 00:48:51.660
And I wouldn't worry so much.

00:48:51.660 --> 00:48:54.122
Vitamin D is a pretty innocuous
thing about combining that

00:48:54.122 --> 00:48:55.080
with other supplements.

00:48:55.080 --> 00:48:56.663
I'm not aware that
that's really going

00:48:56.663 --> 00:48:59.310
to create any major
problems for most people.

00:48:59.310 --> 00:48:59.814
JACK: Cool.

00:48:59.814 --> 00:49:01.439
Question here in the
front, we have a--

00:49:01.439 --> 00:49:01.939
great.

00:49:05.930 --> 00:49:07.880
AUDIENCE: Hi, this is
Alexis [INAUDIBLE]..

00:49:07.880 --> 00:49:09.060
Thank you so much, Dean.

00:49:09.060 --> 00:49:10.460
I have a question around sleep.

00:49:10.460 --> 00:49:11.680
We haven't touched on that.

00:49:11.680 --> 00:49:14.180
And I think all of us
would agree that it's

00:49:14.180 --> 00:49:15.190
increasingly important.

00:49:15.190 --> 00:49:17.065
And it's, in fact, one
of the most important.

00:49:17.065 --> 00:49:18.330
So what are your thoughts?

00:49:18.330 --> 00:49:20.270
DEAN ORNISH: Well,
sleep is one of the ways

00:49:20.270 --> 00:49:22.139
that your brain
detoxifies itself.

00:49:22.139 --> 00:49:23.930
And so there are a lot
of people who think,

00:49:23.930 --> 00:49:25.388
I don't need much
sleep, and so on.

00:49:25.388 --> 00:49:28.070
But Bill Clinton famously
said that the worst decisions

00:49:28.070 --> 00:49:30.079
he ever made were when
he was sleep-deprived.

00:49:30.079 --> 00:49:32.120
And I think Arianna
Huffington has done a of work

00:49:32.120 --> 00:49:34.369
in raising the awareness
about the importance of that.

00:49:34.369 --> 00:49:38.450
So I think if you want to really
be creative and innovative,

00:49:38.450 --> 00:49:40.410
as opposed to imitative,
try to get more sleep.

00:49:40.410 --> 00:49:41.990
It can really make
a big difference.

00:49:41.990 --> 00:49:43.130
JACK: Yeah, I think what's
interesting about sleep

00:49:43.130 --> 00:49:45.920
also is that we don't
fully know the science yet

00:49:45.920 --> 00:49:47.046
of how sleep is helping us.

00:49:47.046 --> 00:49:48.545
And so I think a
lot of times, we're

00:49:48.545 --> 00:49:50.480
willing to cut corners
on sleep, because we

00:49:50.480 --> 00:49:54.350
don't have that immediate
knowledge about what

00:49:54.350 --> 00:49:58.766
is actually happening in
the brain during the sleep.

00:49:58.766 --> 00:50:00.140
But obviously,
it's now come out.

00:50:00.140 --> 00:50:01.200
And it's very clear
from many studies.

00:50:01.200 --> 00:50:02.450
DEAN ORNISH: Well, I think,
even from an evolutionary

00:50:02.450 --> 00:50:04.880
standpoint, why would we
evolve to do something that's

00:50:04.880 --> 00:50:06.830
going to make us use
up so much of our life,

00:50:06.830 --> 00:50:09.540
make us completely vulnerable to
predators while we're sleeping,

00:50:09.540 --> 00:50:10.840
unless it was really important.

00:50:10.840 --> 00:50:12.430
And I think that's
part of why when

00:50:12.430 --> 00:50:14.180
I'm in the middle of
the night and wanting

00:50:14.180 --> 00:50:16.805
to get up and do work, I have to
remind myself of these things.

00:50:16.805 --> 00:50:18.080
[CHUCKLES]

00:50:18.080 --> 00:50:19.820
JACK: Exactly, great.

00:50:19.820 --> 00:50:21.320
We have one more
question back here.

00:50:26.900 --> 00:50:29.060
AUDIENCE: Hi, my
name is [INAUDIBLE]..

00:50:29.060 --> 00:50:31.880
My question is about the
prescription, the four pillars

00:50:31.880 --> 00:50:33.440
which you mentioned.

00:50:33.440 --> 00:50:38.300
Does that change based on the
ethnicity or the underlying

00:50:38.300 --> 00:50:40.130
problem which a person
is trying to treat,

00:50:40.130 --> 00:50:42.850
like obesity or heart disease
or cancer or those things?

00:50:42.850 --> 00:50:43.250
Or is it all [INAUDIBLE]?

00:50:43.250 --> 00:50:44.330
DEAN ORNISH: Not really so much.

00:50:44.330 --> 00:50:45.810
I mean, we fine-tune
a little bit.

00:50:45.810 --> 00:50:48.560
Some people can metabolize
refined carbohydrates or gluten

00:50:48.560 --> 00:50:50.185
or things like that
better than others.

00:50:50.185 --> 00:50:52.740
But for the vast majority
of it, it's really the same.

00:50:52.740 --> 00:50:55.340
And when I started doing
this work, I predicted--

00:50:55.340 --> 00:50:56.930
incorrectly, as it turns out--

00:50:56.930 --> 00:50:59.060
that the younger people
who had less severe disease

00:50:59.060 --> 00:51:00.150
would do better.

00:51:00.150 --> 00:51:02.000
And what we found,
it wasn't a function

00:51:02.000 --> 00:51:03.255
of age or disease severity.

00:51:03.255 --> 00:51:05.630
It was simply a function of
the more you change your diet

00:51:05.630 --> 00:51:07.100
and lifestyle in these
areas, the more you

00:51:07.100 --> 00:51:08.720
improve in every
metric we looked at

00:51:08.720 --> 00:51:10.511
and every disease we studied.

00:51:10.511 --> 00:51:12.260
Now, there may be ways
of fine-tuning this

00:51:12.260 --> 00:51:13.010
as we learn more.

00:51:13.010 --> 00:51:15.200
But what I'm still
so struck by is

00:51:15.200 --> 00:51:17.390
that these same
lifestyle changes,

00:51:17.390 --> 00:51:21.220
the more diseases we study and
the more biological mechanisms

00:51:21.220 --> 00:51:23.090
we research, the
more reasons we have

00:51:23.090 --> 00:51:24.590
to explain why they
are so powerful.

00:51:24.590 --> 00:51:26.060
And it's so hard for a
lot of people to believe,

00:51:26.060 --> 00:51:27.970
like, you mean talking
about my feelings

00:51:27.970 --> 00:51:29.010
is going to help me live longer?

00:51:29.010 --> 00:51:29.630
Are you kidding me?

00:51:29.630 --> 00:51:30.950
[CHUCKLES] Is that
the best you can do?

00:51:30.950 --> 00:51:32.870
It's like, yeah, as a
matter of fact, it is.

00:51:32.870 --> 00:51:34.970
I mean, David Spiegel
did a landmark study

00:51:34.970 --> 00:51:37.100
at Stanford years ago,
where he took women

00:51:37.100 --> 00:51:39.764
with metastatic breast
cancer, randomized them

00:51:39.764 --> 00:51:40.430
into two groups.

00:51:40.430 --> 00:51:42.054
Both groups were
getting the same chemo

00:51:42.054 --> 00:51:43.176
and radiation and surgery.

00:51:43.176 --> 00:51:45.050
But one group had a
support group once a week

00:51:45.050 --> 00:51:46.480
for an hour and a
half for a year,

00:51:46.480 --> 00:51:47.780
in the same way as we
were talking about.

00:51:47.780 --> 00:51:48.860
And then they stopped.

00:51:48.860 --> 00:51:51.020
Five years later, he told me
he almost fell off his chair

00:51:51.020 --> 00:51:52.145
when he looked at the data.

00:51:52.145 --> 00:51:53.720
Those women lived twice as long.

00:51:53.720 --> 00:51:55.490
So these simple
things can really

00:51:55.490 --> 00:51:57.240
make a powerful difference.

00:51:57.240 --> 00:51:57.770
JACK: Great.

